{ Welcome To The Quickstarter Guide   In this Quickstarter guide I'm taking you through the main lines that you can expect to face when playing the Kalashnikov. This will give you enough information to be able to start playing the opening without going through the entire course. I would also strongly recommend that you go through the model games to give yourself an overview of strategy. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5. Nb3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black is able to develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@ . }
5... Nf6 6. Bg5 Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing to castle. } 7. Nc3 O-O
{ Safe and sound.   Incidentally,  7...Nxe4  is a mistake in this position:  8.Nxe4  Bxg5  9.Nd6+  Kf8  10.Bc4  , and Black can barely move. }
8. Bxf6
{ White takes control over the d5 square. No problem! We are used to that in the Kalashnikov. In return, we get the two bishops. This exchange is played at the right moment - before Black gets a chance with a trick. }
8... Bxf6 9. Nd5 d6
{ Here is a big divide. What does White do with the king's bishop? } 10. Bc4
{ Supporting the knight. I think this is White's best move here. } 10... Bg5
{ The bishop moves to a strong diagonal. } 11. O-O Kh8
{ The king steps away from the bishop on c4. This means that the pawn break ...f5 becomes a possibility @@StartBracket@@but be careful with this push, it can harm Black's position by spoiling the pawn structure@@EndBracket@@. the position is very similar to Sveshnikov positions except that White's knight stands on b3 rather than a3. }
12. Qe2 f5
{ Black can also play more calmly with ...Be6 and ...Rc8, but I like this aggression :@@EndBracket@@ }
13. exf5 Bxf5
{ In exchanging off the pawn on e4, White avoids the pawn storm with ...f4, but allows Black excellent piece activity. Look at those beautiful bishops! }
14. Rad1 Ne7
{ Exchanging off the knight will allow Black's queen to reach the b6 square - a very tasty spot looking at b2 and f2. }
15. Nxe7 Qxe7 16. Bd5 Qc7 17. c3 Qb6
{ White's problem is that the knight on b3 is poorly placed. Given time, Black would like to double rooks on the f-file to increase the pressure on f2. }
