[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5.Nb3 Nf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black is able to develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@ . }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ This natural move, played by the vast majority, gives Black a very easy game.   6.Bg5  is a better move, fighting for control over the d5 square. }
6... Bb4
{ There are three ideas behind this move: the e-pawn is threatened; Black threatens to exchange on c3 damaging the structure; and it might be possible to advance the d7 pawn to d5 as Black has neutralised the knight. After this, White is struggling to equalise the position - after just six 'normal' moves! }
7. Bd3 d5
{ In this position, Black has decent prospects if he plays positionally with  7...Bxc3+  8.bxc3  d6  . Perhaps this is just a matter of taste. But I prefer the more straightforward and thematic pawn break. }
8. exd5 { All my opponents played this - even though it is not the best move. }
8... Nxd5
{ Threatening to take the knight on c3. White should defend the knight. } 9.
Bd2 Nxc3 { This exchange damages White's pawn structure. } 10. bxc3
{ White gains a little time by pushing the bishop back. } 10... Bd6
{ The bishop drops back to an active square and can be supported by the queen on c7, with pressure on the diagonal.  Incidentally, instead of the eminently sensible  10...Bd6  my computer recommends the outlandish  10...Ba3  . No thank you: I am not a number, I am a human being. }
11. O-O O-O
{ With both sides castled and the middlegame about to begin, we can take stock of the position: what an outcome for Black! White's queenside pawns are chronically weak. Black has a greater share of the centre with the pawn on e5, and there is a chance to roll down the board with the e and f pawns together attacking White's king. Over 70 games in my database start from this position with results massively in Black's favour. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5.Nb3 Nf6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black is able to develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@ . }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ This natural move, played by the vast majority, gives Black a very easy game.   6.Bg5  is a better move, fighting for control over the d5 square. }
6... Bb4
{ There are three ideas behind this move: the e-pawn is threatened; Black threatens to exchange on c3 damaging the structure; and it might be possible to advance the d7 pawn to d5 as Black has neutralised the knight. After this, White is struggling to equalise the position - after just six 'normal' moves! }
7. Bc4
{ Rapid development to the most active square is, as usual, the most testing. Having said that, if played correctly, Black has more than a satisfactory position. }
7... O-O
{ Let's keep things simple and castle.   In fact, it is possible to capture on e4. The mainline runs:  7...Nxe4  8.Bxf7+  Kxf7  9.Qd5+  Ke8  10.Qxe4  d5  11.Qe2  d4  12.a3  Be7  13.Ne4  Bf5  which is roughly level.  Which option you go for at this point is more a question of taste than anything else. I am recommending castling because it keeps more tension in the position. }
8. O-O Bxc3
{ It's the last chance to damage the pawns before the knight hops into d5. } 9.
bxc3
{ At this point, Black has a fundamental decision to make: hold the structure with  9...d6  and look long-term to play against White's damaged queenside pawns; or grab the pawn in the middle. Once again, I think this is a question of taste - both are objectively fine - but I am going to recommend ambitious pawn grabbing! }
9... Nxe4
{ Not only is Black a pawn up, but White's queenside pawns are shattered. White has some piece play @@StartBracket@@the bishops look good@@EndBracket@@, but if Black can consolidate, the future looks good. }
10. Ba3 { The bishops sear across the position: they need to be neutralised. }
10... d6 11. Qd3
{ This is the most common move played here. The knight should retreat, but that is okay: it returns to a solid square. }
11... Nf6 { A solid square. } 12. Bxd6
{ Looks frightening at first sight, but Black is actually doing well.   Alternatively, the endgame after  12.Qxd6  Qxd6  13.Bxd6  Rd8  14.Ba3  Nd5  is comfortably better for Black because of White's damaged queenside pawns. }
12... Bf5 { A little tactic that simplifies the position. } 13. Qxf5
{ If  13.Qd2  Ne4  wins material, and  13.Qd1  Bxc2  wins a pawn. } 13... Qxd6
{ With one of White's bishops exchanged life is a lot easier for Black. His superior pawn structure gives him the better chances. The shattered queenside pawns are the big problem for White in this line: once the initiative disappears, Black will always stand better in the endgames. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5. Nf3 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nf3
{ This is not the most threatening reply. Where can the knight go from here? In fact, because it is now Black's move it is possible to take the initiative straightaway. }
5... Nf6
{ Simple chess. The knight develops to its best square and attacks the e-pawn. Black is already ahead in the race to develop. }
6. Nc3 Bb4
{ Threatening to take on e4. Black is already seizing the initiative. } 7. Bd3
O-O
{ Black can also play  7...d5  but I like the flexibility of castling. The d-pawn might well advance two squares, but there is also another plan available, namely exchanging on c3, then playing d6 and exploiting the weak doubled c-pawns. Let's see how White plays then react accordingly. }
8. O-O
{ Instead,  8.Bg5  Bxc3+  9.bxc3  d6  should transpose to the line that starts with  8.O-O  . }
8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 d6
{ I like this simple move. Black has the superior pawn structure and intends to play on the weak c-pawns. Black's results from this position are excellent.   It is also possible to play  9...d5  , but in this case  10.exd5  Qxd5  11.Ng5  is a bit tricky. }
10. Bg5
{ This pin is the only move that could possibly upset Black's set up, but in fact it can be dealt with easily. }
10... h6
{ It is useful to flick in this move as the bishop must commit to a diagonal. From h4 it no longer has any influence on the queenside. }
11. Bh4 Na5
{ Let's be direct. Black is either going to attack the pawn on c3 or station the knight on c4.   By the way, don't play  11...g5  , the sacrifice  12.Nxg5  hxg5  13.Bxg5  gives White more play than he deserves. }
12. Nd2
{ The knight isn't doing much on f3 so it moves to look for a better circuit. }
12... Be6 13. Re1
{ White's options are limited. If  13.f4  exf4  14.Rxf4  g5  wins a piece. }
13... g5 { Now that the knight has moved from f3 this advance is possible. }
14. Bg3 Qc7 { Having driven away the bishop the queen is free to move. } 15. h4
Kg7 16. Nf1 Qxc3
{ Black is a pawn up and has a safe position. White's kingside aggression could easily rebound as the rooks can transfer to h8 and g8 very easily. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " 5. Nxc6 bxc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nxc6
{ My database indicates that this is the fourth most popular move at this juncture, not far behind  5.Nb3  and  5.Nf3  . I am amazed! What an ugly move!  In general, this exchange is beneficial to Black in the Sicilian, and this position is no exception. Black recaptures with the b-pawn, controlling the crucial d5-square and as a bonus enabling Black to operate on the semi-open b-file. The central pawn majority is a very real asset for Black, not just in the middlegame but also in the endgame.  I only ever faced this early on in my chess career when I encountered players as bad as I was. Of course, the exchange isn't disastrous for White, but you can already start to question your opponent's positional understanding 😃 }
5... bxc6
{ I have never really questioned this move as it feels so good positionally, but there is nothing wrong with  5...dxc6  either.  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Black's king will sit safely on c7 and the position is roughly level - but not drawn. With so many pieces still on the board, all three results are possible.  How you recapture on c6 is simply a question of taste. If you like endgames, head for this; if you prefer more complexity, pick up the b-pawn. }
6. Bc4
{ Classical development. Does White really imagine he is going to deliver checkmate on f7? Probably not, but it is a good diagonal for the bishop and Black's central pawn push ...d5 has been prevented. }
6... Nf6
{ Simple and strong development is in order. Black doesn't need to play outlandishly to secure a decent position. }
7. Nc3 { White should protect the e-pawn. } 7... Bb4
{ The most testing move, although there is nothing wrong with  7...Be7  and  7...Bc5  . White has to deal with the threat to the  e4  pawn, not to mention the  d5  pawn advance. }
8. O-O Bxc3
{ I think this is the clearest way to play although I should add that I see nothing wrong with  8...O-O }
9. bxc3 O-O
{ 9...Nxe4?!  is a bit greedy. Black's king is still in the middle of the board!  10.Ba3  d5  11.Bd3  Be6  12.Bxe4  dxe4  13.Qh5=∞  and White has enough compensation.   9...d5?!  is in this case premature:  10.exd5  cxd5  11.Bb5+  Bd7  12.Bxd7+  Qxd7  13.Ba3  prevents Black from castling. }
10. Re1 d5
{ This equalises immediately, but if you want to keep more tension in the position, then  10...d6  is fine. Black will follow with  ...Be6  and has the superior pawn structure. The centre pawns are strong! }
11. exd5 cxd5 12. Bb3 Qc7
{ Black has established an impressive centre and looks to be better. White should tackle it straightaway and force exchanges. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " 5. Nf5 d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nf5
{ Doesn't this look menacing? Yes! Is it good? No!  In a just world, we would applaud moving the knight to this excellent outpost, but instead, we can snigger at this futile attempt to upset Black. Launch the d-pawn! Two squares! }
5... d5
{ We can immediately undermine the position of the knight and at a stroke liberate Black's pieces. I suspect that this move is often overlooked, and the shock causes White to make errors. }
6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6
{ By capturing with the queen on d5, White retains the right to castle. Then again, the threat to the c-pawn must be addressed. }
9. Bd3
{ This is probably the most sensible way of dealing with the threat. White is prepared to compromise his pawn structure in order to relieve the pressure.   Instead,  9.c3  is quite an ugly move, taking away the c3-square from the knight and weakening d3. Black should simply develop normally afterwards:  9...Nf6  .   9.Ba6  also doesn't improve the position:  9...Rb8  just means that the bishop on c1 cannot develop. }
9... Bxd3
{ Losing no time and damaging White's pawn structure. Black can also play  9...Bb4+  10.Bd2  Bxd3  11.cxd3  a5  and chances are balanced.   I don't like  9...e4  10.Bc4  which leaves the bishop on f5 blocked. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "5. Ne2 Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Ne2
{ This is too sophisticated. Blocking the king's bishop can't be a good idea. Did no one tell the player of the white pieces that time is of the essence in the opening? By contrast, Black's development is classical and straightforward. }
5... Nf6
{ Threatening the e-pawn. Good start. Black is already ahead in development! }
6. Nbc3
{ White defends the e-pawn and also takes a little control over the d5 square. There is no immediate pressure on Black's position, which allows a choice of where to place the king's bishop. }
6... Bc5
{ 6...Bb4  is also possible, but playing the bishop to c5 is the most dangerous, looking down at one of the weakest squares on the board. I sense tricks. }
7. Ng3
{ White had better hurry up and clear the traffic jam.   Instead,  7.g3  allows  7...Ng4  - winning! }
7... O-O 8. Bc4 d6 9. O-O
{ At this juncture, Black has a pleasant choice.  9...a6  is sensible, ensuring that the bishop has a safe place to retreat if attacked by Na4.   9...Be6  is also sound, contesting the d5-square.  In both cases, chances are balanced.   But there is also a tricky move that heaps the pressure on your opponent. In order to hold the position, he has to play precisely. }
9... Ng4 { Black attacks! The queen is on the way to h4... } 10. h3
{ Hoping the knight will drop back, but... } 10... Qh4
{ with complications... } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " 5. Nb5 d6 6th move sidelines #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ That already looks pleasant from Black's viewpoint. The knight has been sent back to a poor square. Much of the subsequent opening and middlegame struggle will centre on whether that knight can transfer to a decent square. }
7... Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nd5 Nf6
{ This simple development demonstrates the problem with White's last move: the knight on  d5  is challenged and the e-pawn threatened, inducing a compromise. At this point, White has several continuations, with  9.Nxf6+  the most popular move. In my opinion, none of the moves give any advantage, and in several cases, White has to struggle to avoid falling into a poor position }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " 5. Nb5 d6 6th move sidelines #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ That already looks pleasant from Black's viewpoint. The knight has been sent back to a poor square. Much of the subsequent opening and middlegame struggle will centre on whether that knight can transfer to a decent square. }
7... Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nc4 b5
{ Forcing the knight to move again. This is overwhelmingly the most popular move.   Instead  8...Nf6  runs into  9.Bg5  with the threat to take on  f6  . }
9. Ne3
{ From White's viewpoint, the position has improved because the errant knight on a3 has succeeded in finding a better home on e3. But Black can also be content: the knight manoeuvres have cost White much time. }
9... Nf6
{ This is the starting point of the mainline of the 7... Be7 variation. From here there are four main moves:  10.a3  ,  10.Ned5  ,  10.Bd3  ,  10.g3  . }
10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O
{ Both sides have castled and the middlegame begins. Black has gained space on the queenside with the advance of the b-pawn and in an ideal world would like to build pressure on the c-file with ...Be6 and ...Rc8. For the time being, that will have to wait. Let's hassle the bishop first. }
11... Nb4
{ Exchanging off the light-squared bishop is desirable for Black: key squares in this position are d5, f5, e4, and c2 - all on light squares. Once the bishop is gone, the fight tips towards Black. }
12. a3 Nxd3 13. Qxd3 Be6
{ In principle, this is what Black wants: the way is clear to build up pressure on the queenside and it is very hard for White to win undisputed control over the d5 square. }
