8. Na3 g6
{ In the early days of the Kalashnikov, most players developed their bishop to e7, but the fianchetto is far more dynamic. This has been championed by the Iranian prodigy Parham Maghsoodloo. }
9. Nc2
{ Move order is flexible. Most players like to play the knight to c2 to cover the d4 square - and I think that is the most sensible.   Others prefer to develop with  9.Be3  or  9.Be2  . Very often these lines transpose. I will point out where these variations have independent significance. From Black's viewpoint matters are much clearer: in most cases, the next moves will be ...Bg7, ...Nf6, ...O-O - and then let's think again! }
9... Bg7 10. Be3 Nf6
{ This is the best square for the knight, putting pressure on the e4 pawn, looking at the g4 square, perhaps moving to h5, and covering the d5 square. In the old days of this variation, Black automatically put the knight on e7, but it is far less effective there as it cannot find another good square to move to. }
11. Be2 { The bishop prevents the knight from moving to g4 and h5. } 11... O-O
12. O-O
{ Both sides have developed sensibly and brought their kings to safety. Let the middlegame battle begin! }
12... Rc8
{ This is where the rook belongs. The c-file is going to be a great source of counterplay for Black. In the past, such positions were thought to be better for White because of the supposedly weak pawn on d6. Let's reframe our thinking. This is a kind of Hedgehog position where with a couple of pawn breaks Black's pieces will be unleashed. }
13. b3
{ This position was reached in two games: Steinberg-Cheparinov and Anand-Maghsoodloo. Both ended in spectacular victories for Black. This is an important moment in the game. If White can hold his center together he will be in control of the position. But Black can hit out at the enemy structure immediately. }
13... b5
{ This pawn break will be familiar to anyone that plays the Hedgehog. Getting rid of the c4 pawn opens up the c-file and the rook on c8 menaces White's knights. More than that, the d5 pawn break is coming soon to let loose Black's pieces. }
14. cxb5 { If White does not take then the c4 pawn will become isolated. }
14... axb5
{ This is the most accurate move, although there is an interesting alternative,  14...Ne7  , played in the fascinating game Anand-Maghsoodloo. This is examined in the 'Model Games' chapter. }
15. Nxb5 Nxe4
{ A good trade: Black gives up a side pawn @@StartBracket@@or two@@EndBracket@@ for a center pawn. }
16. f3 Nf6 { The knight has to retreat. } 17. Nxd6
{ White has managed to grab the important d-pawn, but Black has excellent compensation. }
17... Ra8 { A good square for the rook putting pressure on the a2 pawn. } 18.
Ne4 { The knight blocks the e-pawn from advancing. } 18... Qc7
{ preparing to bring a rook into the middle to attack the queen. } 19. Qe1 Nxe4
20. fxe4 Nd4
{ Black has the superior pawn structure, active pieces, and a safer king than White. In other words, excellent compensation for the pawn. }
