[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Kalashnikov 5.Nb3"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb3 - 6.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black can develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6 6. Bg5 Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing to castle. } 7. Nc3 O-O
{ Safe and sound.   Incidentally,  7...Nxe4  is a mistake in this position:  8.Nxe4  Bxg5  9.Nd6+  Kf8  10.Bc4  , and Black can barely move. }
8. Bc4 { This looks normal, but in fact, it allows a trick. } 8... Nxe4
{ A standard tactical ploy. } 9. Bxe7 Nxc3
{ Black has to keep taking - the knight attacks the queen. } 10. Bxd8
{ Instead  10.bxc3  Qxe7  gives Black a clear extra pawn. } 10... Nxd1 11. Rxd1
{ 11.Bc7  Nxb2  gives Black two extra pawns. } 11... Rxd8 12. Rd6
{ This is the only way for White to get compensation for the pawn: Black is a bit bottled up, but it is possible to lift the blockade. Enter the king. }
12... Kf8 13. O-O Ke7 14. Rfd1
{ The rook has to be supported. If  14.Rd2  d6  and Black is a pawn up with a good position. }
14... f6
{ This prepares to break the blockade. Black needs a strong pawn chain in order to set up the trick. }
15. c3 Nd4 { There it is. The connection between the rooks is broken. } 16.
Nxd4 Kxd6 17. Ne6+ Ke7 18. Nxd8 Kxd8
{ After that forced sequence, Black still has the extra pawn! With a little bit of care, it can be converted into a win. }
*

