[White "1. Kalashnikov 5.Nb3"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb3 - 6.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black can develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6 6. Bg5 Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing to castle. } 7. Nc3 O-O
{ Safe and sound.   Incidentally,  7...Nxe4  is a mistake in this position:  8.Nxe4  Bxg5  9.Nd6+  Kf8  10.Bc4  , and Black can barely move. }
8. Bc4 { This looks normal, but in fact, it allows a trick. } 8... Nxe4
{ A standard tactical ploy. } 9. Nxe4 Bxg5 10. Nd6
{ Black has won a pawn, but White has managed to bring the knight to a strong position. The good news is that Black can get rid of this beast! }
10... Qb6
{ The idea of this is that  11.Qd5  can be strongly met by  11...Nb4  . } 11.
O-O Be7 12. Nxc8
{ By this stage, White should grab the pawn back.   Instead  12.c3  Qc7!  13.Nxc8  Raxc8  .   Or  12.Qd2  Nd4!  That move again, cutting off communication between the White pieces  13.Nxd4  Qxd6  14.Nf3  Qxd2  15.Nxd2  d6  . In both cases with a clear extra pawn. }
12... Raxc8 13. Qxd7
{ White has won back the pawn, but Black is better developed and can take the initiative. }
13... Rcd8 14. Qh3 g6
{ Black's plan is to play ...Kg7 and ...f5 exploiting the kingside pawn majority. }
