[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Kalashnikov 5.Nb3"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb3 - 6.Bg5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black is able to develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6 6. Bg5 Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing to castle. } 7. Nc3 O-O
{ Safe and sound.   Incidentally,  7...Nxe4  is a mistake in this position:  8.Nxe4  Bxg5  9.Nd6+  Kf8  10.Bc4  , and Black can barely move. }
8. Bxf6
{ White takes control over the d5 square. No problem! We are used to that in the Kalashnikov. In return, we get the two bishops. This exchange is played at the right moment - before Black gets a chance with a trick. }
8... Bxf6 9. Nd5 d6
{ Here is a big divide. What does White do with the king's bishop? } 10. c3
{ This can be a useful move for White, taking away the d4 square from the knight. It is also sometimes played as a waiting move, preparing to meet ...Bg5 with aggression. }
10... Bg5
{ As usual, we need to activate the bishop and it moves out of the range of the knight. Here,  11.Bc4  is normal, but occasionally White is tempted to attack. }
11. h4
{ When I see my opponents play like this, I start to cheer inside! In the end, such uncalled-for aggression only harms White's position. }
11... Bh6
{ Nice and calm. And what has the pawn advance achieved? Not a lot, though it does make it harder for White to castle.   If  11...Bxh4  12.Qh5  wins - obviously. }
12. g4
{ Let's assume White is going to follow up consistently and throw pawn number 2 up the board. Really? }
12... f6 { 12...Bf4  is also fine. } 13. Rg1 Be6
{ I don't see how White can make a successful breakthrough and what exactly is to be done with the king in the middle? }
*

