Bd2 Nxc3 { This exchange damages White's pawn structure. } 10. bxc3
{ White gains a little time by pushing the bishop back. } 10... Bd6
{ The bishop drops back to an active square and can be supported by the queen on c7, with pressure on the diagonal.  Incidentally, instead of the eminently sensible  10...Bd6  my computer recommends the outlandish  10...Ba3  . No thank you: I am not a number, I am a human being. }
11. O-O O-O
{ With both sides castled and the middlegame about to begin, let's evaluate the position: what an outcome for Black! White's queenside pawns are chronically weak. Black has a greater share of the centre with the pawn on e5, and there is a chance to roll down the board with the e and f pawns together attacking White's king. Over 70 games in my database start from this position with results massively in Black's favour. }
12. Qh5
{ The queen cannot do much on its own.   If  12.f4  , then  12...f5  Preventing White's f-pawn from advancing, closing the bishop's diagonal towards h7, and claiming some important central control. Black can look forward to the middlegame, and indeed endgame, with confidence. }
12... g6 13. Qh6 Be6
{ Before launching the f-pawn forward, it is best to develop the queenside and coordinate. This bishop prevents White's bishop from moving to c4. }
14. Rae1 Qc7
{ Black is ready to advance the f-pawn, with a distinct advantage in space. There is no rush in these kinds of positions, first control events. White's queenside pawn weaknesses cannot fix themselves. }
