[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb3 - 6.Nc3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black is able to develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ This natural move, played by the vast majority, gives Black a very easy game.   6.Bg5  is a better move, fighting for control over the d5 square. }
6... Bb4
{ There are three ideas behind this move: the e-pawn is threatened; Black threatens to exchange on c3 damaging the structure; and it might be possible to advance the d7 pawn to d5 as Black has neutralised the knight. After this, White is struggling to equalise the position - after just six 'normal' moves! }
7. Bg5
{ As Black's bishop has developed actively, White takes the chance to pin, but this can be dealt with very easily. }
7... h6 { Problem solved! } 8. Bxf6
{ Exchanging is best, but that is an admission of failure for White's strategy. }
8... Bxc3+
{ Let's exchange while we get the chance. It is worth damaging White's queenside pawn structure. }
9. bxc3 Qxf6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O d6
{ If White doesn't create some action, then Black will play the bishop to e6, put the rooks on the c and d files, and eventually arrange to attack the doubled c-pawns. Then again, if White does stir up the position, it often rebounds. }
12. Qd2 Rd8
{ Protecting the d-pawn before playing ...Be6. What can White do? Pressing the d-pawn gets nowhere. Advancing the queenside pawns doesn't achieve anything. I know what all the Sicilian players like to do - fling the f-pawn! }
13. f4
{ Are we worried? Not at all! White has just damaged his pawn structure and provided an excellent square for the knight on e5. }
13... exf4 14. Rxf4 Qe7
{ White's pawn structure is ragged. That is the real difference between the two positions. }
15. Nd4 Ne5
{ The knight holds Black's position together, guarding the f7 pawn, and looking at g4, f3, d3, and c4. It is very difficult for White to mobilise an attack on the kingside while avoiding the tricky beast. }
16. Raf1 Be6
{ When White's queenside pawns are split, Black's plan is usually going to be ...Rac8 and ...Qc7 to attack them. }
17. Nf5 Bxf5 { We shouldn't have to live with that dangerous knight. } 18. exf5
{ The best chance. Instead  18.Rxf5  Rac8  and White has no counterplay. }
18... Qf6
{ Securely blockading the f-pawn. Black is almost ready to attack the pawn on c3 with ...Rac8 and White has to be careful not to fall into a passive position. }
