{  } 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black is able to develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ This natural move, played by the vast majority, gives Black a very easy game.   6.Bg5  is a better move, fighting for control over the d5 square. }
6... Bb4
{ There are three ideas behind this move: the e-pawn is threatened; Black threatens to exchange on c3 damaging the structure; and it might be possible to advance the d7 pawn to d5 as Black has neutralised the knight. After this, White is struggling to equalise the position - after just six 'normal' moves! }
7. Bc4
{ Rapid development to the most active square is, as usual, the most testing. Having said that, if played correctly, Black has more than a satisfactory position. }
7... O-O
{ Let's keep things simple and castle.   In fact, it is possible to capture on e4. The mainline runs:  7...Nxe4  8.Bxf7+  Kxf7  9.Qd5+  Ke8  10.Qxe4  d5  11.Qe2  d4  12.a3  Be7  13.Ne4  Bf5  which is roughly level.  Which option you go for at this point is more a question of taste than anything else. I am recommending castling because it keeps more tension in the position. }
8. Bg5
{ This is similar to @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/pp1p1ppp/2n2n2/4p3/1b2P3/1NN5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 4 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  on the previous turn, but there are a couple of nuances that we need to be aware of. }
8... h6 9. Bh4
{ Instead  9.Bxf6  Bxc3+  10.bxc3  is similar to the last turn. In my opinion, White is already fighting for equality. }
9... Bxc3+
{ For the moment, we should resist advancing the g-pawn:  9...g5?!  10.Bg3  Nxe4  11.Qd3  Nf6?!  12.Qg6+  , Oops. That's a position Black should avoid. But that's no problem, we can fall back on our strategy of calmly developing the queenside. }
10. bxc3 d6 11. Qd3
{ The e-pawn needed protecting. If instead  11.O-O  g5  12.Bg3  Nxe4  is a safe extra pawn. }
11... Qe7 { So that the rook can move to d8 if necessary. } 12. O-O g5
{ Black can safely advance because White cannot bring any pieces to attack on the kingside. }
13. Bg3 Be6
{ Black is in control of the game with chances to attack on the kingside or queenside depending on how White plays. }
