[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb3 - 6.Nc3 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb3
{ In my experience, this is a common move. I have a feeling that many players have seen in other Sicilian positions that the knight ends up on b3, and so plonk it there through learned habit. In fact, in this case, the knight is somewhat misplaced and Black is able to develop easily and even take over the initiative @@StartBracket@@if White is careless@@EndBracket@@. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ This natural move, played by the vast majority, gives Black a very easy game.   6.Bg5  is a better move, fighting for control over the d5 square. }
6... Bb4
{ There are three ideas behind this move: the e-pawn is threatened; Black threatens to exchange on c3 damaging the structure; and it might be possible to advance the d7 pawn to d5 as Black has neutralised the knight. After this, White is struggling to equalise the position - after just six 'normal' moves! }
7. Bc4
{ Rapid development to the most active square is, as usual, the most testing. Having said that, if played correctly, Black has more than a satisfactory position. }
7... O-O
{ Let's keep things simple and castle.   In fact, it is possible to capture on e4. The mainline runs:  7...Nxe4  8.Bxf7+  Kxf7  9.Qd5+  Ke8  10.Qxe4  d5  11.Qe2  d4  12.a3  Be7  13.Ne4  Bf5  which is roughly level.  Which option you go for at this point is more a question of taste than anything else. I am recommending castling because it keeps more tension in the position. }
8. O-O Bxc3
{ It's the last chance to damage the pawns before the knight hops into d5. } 9.
bxc3
{ At this point, Black has a fundamental decision to make: hold the structure with  9...d6  and look long-term to play against White's damaged queenside pawns; or grab the pawn in the middle. Once again, I think this is a question of taste - both are objectively fine - but I am going to recommend ambitious pawn grabbing! }
9... Nxe4
{ Not only is Black a pawn up but White's queenside pawns are shattered. White has some piece play @@StartBracket@@the bishops look good@@EndBracket@@, but if Black can consolidate, the future looks good. }
10. Ba3 { The bishops sear across the position: they need to be neutralised. }
10... d6 11. Qe1 { After this Black will have a little defending to do. } 11...
Nf6 { A necessary retreat. } 12. Rd1 Re8
{ Black could retreat the knight to e8 to defend the d-pawn, but I prefer not to go backward. The aim is to quell White's activity and exploit the superior pawn structure. }
13. Bxd6 Bf5 { Threatening the pawn on c2. Black develops with tempo. } 14. Qe2
a6
{ Threatening to drive away the bishop with ...b5. If  15.Bxe5  Qb6  wins a piece because of the pin on the e-file. }
15. a4
{ Dragging the a-pawn up the board is a cute idea: on a4 it is more of a target later on in the game. }
15... Qc8
{ The queen steps away from the line of White's rook and sets up the threat of ...Ne4. }
16. h3 { Instead,  16.f3  e4  17.fxe4?  Bg4  is winning for Black. } 16... Ne4
17. Qe3 Nxd6 18. Rxd6 Qc7
{ Every exchange eases the pressure and with his superior pawn structure Black stands better. }
*

