10. Ba3 { The bishops sear across the position: they need to be neutralised. }
10... d6 11. Qd3
{ This is the most common move played here. The knight should retreat, but that is okay: it returns to a solid square. }
11... Nf6 { A solid square. } 12. Bxd6
{ Looks frightening at first sight, but Black is actually doing well.   Alternatively, the endgame after  12.Qxd6  Qxd6  13.Bxd6  Rd8  14.Ba3  Nd5  is comfortably better for Black because of White's damaged queenside pawns. }
12... Bf5 { A little tactic that simplifies the position. } 13. Qxf5
{ If  13.Qd2  Ne4  wins material, and  13.Qd1  Bxc2  wins a pawn. } 13... Qxd6
{ With one of White's bishops exchanged life is a lot easier for Black. His superior pawn structure gives him better chances. The shattered queenside pawns are the big problem for White in this line: once the initiative disappears, Black will always stand better in the endgames. }
