1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nf3
{ This is not the most threatening reply. Where can the knight go from here? In fact, because it is now Black's move it is possible to take the initiative straight away. }
5... Nf6
{ Simple chess. The knight develops to its best square and attacks the e-pawn. Black is already ahead in the race to develop. }
6. Bg5
{ Black could just respond with  6...Be7  , but I feel that more aggressive development is in order. }
6... Bc5
{ That's a nice diagonal for the bishop, looking at the f2 square. White must take care! }
7. Nc3 Qb6
{ Black seizes the initiative. Two pawns are attacked and White must play very carefully. If  8.Bxf6  Bxf2+  9.Kd2  Qe3  is checkmate! }
8. Bc4 Qxb2
{ Can Black get away with this? Definitely! The tactics work as White's king is still in the middle and the minor pieces are loose on c3 and c4. }
9. Bd2 Qb6 { The queen MUST get back to safety. } 10. Na4
{ A mistake. It might win a piece, but it leaves White with a wretched position. }
10... Bxf2+ 11. Kf1 Qc7 12. Kxf2 Nxe4+ 13. Kf1 Ne7
{ Gaining a tempo against the bishop on c4. } 14. Qe2 Nxd2+ 15. Nxd2 d5 16. Bb3
O-O
{ For the piece Black has three pawns, a great centre, and the chance to attack the displaced king on f1. My computer believes that Black already has a winning advantage, and I am inclined to believe it. }
