1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nf3
{ This is not the most threatening reply. Where can the knight go from here? In fact, because it is now Black's move it is possible to take the initiative straight away. }
5... Nf6
{ Simple chess. The knight develops to its best square and attacks the e-pawn. Black is already ahead in the race to develop. }
6. Bc4 { White forgot to defend the e-pawn! } 6... Nxe4 7. Qd5 Qa5+
{ This is a matter of taste, but I would prefer to return the pawn and achieve a decent position rather than hang on to my booty and risk all.   But if the latter is your thing, then please go ahead with  7...Nd6  8.Bb3  f6  9.O-O  b6  10.Nc3  Bb7  . White obviously has compensation for the pawn by occupying d5, and for a time the king must remain in the centre, but the computer assesses this position as better for Black. }
8. Qxa5 Nxa5 9. Nxe5 Nxc4 10. Nxc4 d5 11. Ncd2 Be6
{ With the two bishops and easy development, Black can look forward with confidence. }
