1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nf3
{ This is not the most threatening reply. Where can the knight go from here? In fact, because it is now Black's move it is possible to take the initiative straight away. }
5... Nf6
{ Simple chess. The knight develops to its best square and attacks the e-pawn. Black is already ahead in the race to develop. }
6. Nc3 Bb4
{ Threatening to take on e4. Black is already seizing the initiative. } 7. Bc4
O-O
{ Once the bishop moves to  c4  , it's important to take the king out of the middle and protect the  f7  square. Instead,  7...Nxe4  8.Qd5  Nd6  9.Bb3  gives White too much play. It isn't worth taking the pawn if the smooth flow of development is spoiled. }
8. Bg5 h6
{ As usual, it is worth including this pawn move to drive the bishop away from the queenside. }
9. Bh4
{ 9.Bxf6  Bxc3+  10.bxc3  Qxf6  is more than fine for Black: the queen is well placed on f6 and White has nothing to compensate for his poor pawn structure. }
9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 d6 11. Qd3 Na5 12. Bb3 Qe7 13. O-O Rd8
{ The d-pawn is easily defended, then Black can follow with all the usual moves: ...Be6, Rac8, with pressure on the pawns. }
