O-O
{ Black can also play  7...d5  but I like the flexibility of castling. The d-pawn might well advance two squares, but there is also another plan available, namely exchanging on c3, then playing d6 and exploiting the weak doubled c-pawns. Let's see how White plays then react accordingly. }
8. Bd2
{ This prevents Black from damaging the pawns, but is passive. Break out time. }
8... d5
{ Boom! Doesn't that look good? White's king is still in the middle - let's give the bottle a shake. }
9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Bxb4
{ Instead  11.O-O  e4  wins a piece for Black. } 11... Nxb4
{ The knight defends the queen so no discovered check:@@EndBracket@@ } 12. Be2
Qe4 13. O-O Bg4 { Black already stands better. The threat is ...Rad8. } *

