1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nxc6
{ My database indicates that this is the fourth most popular move at this juncture, not far behind  5.Nb3  and  5.Nf3  . I am amazed! What an ugly move!  In general, this exchange is beneficial to Black in the Sicilian, and this position is no exception. Black recaptures with the b-pawn, controlling the crucial d5-square and as a bonus enabling Black to operate on the semi-open b-file. The central pawn majority is a very real asset for Black, not just in the middlegame but also in the endgame.  I only ever faced this early on in my chess career when I encountered players as bad as I was. Of course, the exchange isn't disastrous for White, but you can already start to question your opponent's positional understanding 😃 }
5... bxc6
{ I have never really questioned this move as it feels so good positionally, but there is nothing wrong with  5...dxc6  either.  6.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Black's king will sit safely on c7 and the position is roughly level - but not drawn. With so many pieces still on the board, all three results are possible.  How you recapture on c6 is simply a question of taste. If you like endgames, head for this; if you prefer more complexity, pick up the b-pawn. }
6. Bc4
{ Classical development. Does White really imagine he is going to deliver checkmate on f7? Probably not, but it is a good diagonal for the bishop and Black's central pawn push ...d5 has been prevented. }
6... Ba6
{ can also be considered. It would probably come as quite a surprise for many playing this variation. If White reacts timidly then Black can reach a pleasant position. However, playing for the attack is much stronger: }
7. Bxa6 Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Qxa6 9. Qh5
{ 9.Qe2  Qxe2+  10.Kxe2  Bb4  followed by ...Nf6 and ...Ke7 is a pleasant endgame considering that Black has a central pawn majority. }
9... d6 10. Bg5 Rb8 11. O-O-O
{ gives White the initiative, and there is no need for Black to play like this. }
*

