[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nf5
{ Doesn't this look menacing? Yes! Is it good? No!  In a just world, we would applaud moving the knight to this excellent outpost, but instead, we can snigger at this futile attempt to upset Black. Launch the d-pawn! Two squares! }
5... d5
{ We can immediately undermine the position of the knight and at a stroke liberate Black's pieces. I suspect that this move is often overlooked, and the shock causes White to make errors. }
6. exd5 { This is the worst of the two options. } 6... Bxf5 7. dxc6 Qxd1+ 8.
Kxd1 bxc6
{ White can probably still equalise if he is careful, but with the king stuck in the middle of the board, even without queens, the odds are in Black's favour. }
9. Bd3 e4
{ Instead,  9...Bxd3  10.cxd3  is roughly level, but I think Black should press for more. }
10. Bc4 { Instead, if  10.Re1  O-O-O  wins for Black! } 10... O-O-O+ 11. Ke2
Bg4+ { White's king is caught in a storm of checks and the position opens up. }
12. f3 exf3+ 13. gxf3 Bh5 14. Nc3 Bc5
{ If White isn't careful, the king will be caught in a crossfire. Black can attack without pressure - after all, these developing moves are very natural - and even if it doesn't come off he has lost nothing as his pawn structure is perfectly sound. Watch out for ...Nf6 and ...Rhe8+; or simply ...Re8+ straightaway. }
