[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Kalashnikov 5.Nf5"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nf5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nf5
{ Doesn't this look menacing? Yes! Is it good? No!  In a just world, we would applaud moving the knight to this excellent outpost, but instead, we can snigger at this futile attempt to upset Black. Launch the d-pawn! Two squares! }
5... d5
{ We can immediately undermine the position of the knight and at a stroke liberate Black's pieces. I suspect that this move is often overlooked, and the shock causes White to make errors. }
6. Qxd5 Qxd5 7. exd5 Bxf5 8. dxc6 bxc6
{ By capturing with the queen on d5, White retains the right to castle. Then again, the threat to the c-pawn must be addressed. }
9. Bd3
{ This is probably the most sensible way of dealing with the threat. White is prepared to compromise his pawn structure in order to relieve the pressure.   Instead,  9.c3  is quite an ugly move, taking away the c3-square from the knight and weakening d3. Black should simply develop normally afterwards:  9...Nf6  .   9.Ba6  also doesn't improve the position:  9...Rb8  just means that the bishop on c1 cannot develop. }
9... Bxd3
{ Losing no time and damaging White's pawn structure. Black can also play  9...Bb4+  10.Bd2  Bxd3  11.cxd3  a5  and chances are balanced.   I don't like  9...e4  10.Bc4  which leaves the bishop on f5 blocked. }
10. cxd3 Nf6
{ Let's keep things simple: develop the knight and think about the other pieces afterwards. }
11. Nc3 Nd5
{ The knight stands well in the middle of the board.   By the way, instead of  11...Nd5  , Black could also choose  11...Bc5  and  11...Kd7  , for example. That's an indication that Black's position is comfortable. }
12. Ke2
{ Instead of this,  12.O-O  O-O-O  applies pressure to the d3 pawn. That's why White's king should remain in the middle.   12.Nxd5  cxd5  leaves Black with greater central control. }
12... Kd7 13. Be3 Rb8
{ Black has some pressure on the b-file, a little space advantage, and there is still plenty of play left in this endgame. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5. Kalashnikov 5.Ne2"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Ne2 - 6.Nec3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Ne2
{ This is too sophisticated. Blocking the king's bishop can't be a good idea. Did no one tell the player of the white pieces that time is of the essence in the opening? By contrast, Black's development is classical and straightforward. }
5... Nf6
{ Threatening the e-pawn. Good start. Black is already ahead in development! }
6. Nec3
{ I understand White's desire to free the bishop on f1, but moving this knight to c3 just creates another traffic jam. }
6... Bc5
{ The bishop hits an excellent diagonal, pointing at f2. This is particularly strong now that there aren't many defenders on the kingside. }
7. Bc4 d6 8. a3
{ This careless move was played in the game Weenink-Sultan Khan, Hamburg 1930. White has taken his queenside footling to extremes. }
8... Ng4
{ This early attack is incredibly powerful. If  9.O-O  Qh4  attacks h2 and f2 - winning. }
9. Be3 { Black has a pleasant choice of captures. } 9... Bxe3
{ This is the best move, although a few tactics have to be negotiated. } 10.
fxe3 Nxe3 11. Bxf7+
{ This is White's only chance to muddy the waters. Instead,  11.Qd3  Nd4  , attacking c2, is tremendous for Black. }
11... Kf8 { Instead, } 12. Qf3 Nd4 13. Qf2 Nexc2+ 14. Kd2 Nxa1
{ leaves Black a rook up - there is no decent discovered check for White. } *

