[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Ne2
{ This is too sophisticated. Blocking the king's bishop can't be a good idea. Did no one tell the player of the white pieces that time is of the essence in the opening? By contrast, Black's development is classical and straightforward. }
5... Nf6
{ Threatening the e-pawn. Good start. Black is already ahead in development! }
6. Nec3
{ I understand White's desire to free the bishop on f1, but moving this knight to c3 just creates another traffic jam. }
6... Bc5
{ The bishop hits an excellent diagonal, pointing at f2. This is particularly strong now that there aren't many defenders on the kingside. }
7. Bc4 d6 8. O-O Be6
{ This is the way to deal with a bishop on c4: offer an exchange that will improve Black's pawn structure. The bishop also covers the d5 square. }
9. Nd2 a6
{ This ensures that the dark-squared bishop remains on this excellent diagonal: if the knight goes to a4, the bishop drops back to a7. Apart from that, it may be a good idea to expand on the queenside with ...b5 at some later stage. }
10. Bb3 O-O 11. Nf3 h6
{ An optically normal position has arisen, but the white knights have taken four moves to get to squares they can normally get to in one jump! With two extra tempi, Black's position is more than satisfactory.  Naturally, one has to take into account White's moves, but as Black, I would be considering plans such as ...Rc8, ...b5, ...Na5 in some order. Or ...Qc7, ... Rfd8. For White, development isn't so simple. }
*

