{ White defends the e-pawn and also takes a little control over the d5 square. There is no immediate pressure on Black's position, which allows a choice of where to place the king's bishop. }
6... Bc5
{ 6...Bb4  is also possible, but playing the bishop to c5 is the most dangerous, looking down at one of the weakest squares on the board. I sense tricks. }
7. Ng3
{ White had better hurry up and clear the traffic jam.   Instead,  7.g3  allows  7...Ng4  - winning! }
7... O-O 8. Bc4 d6 9. Na4
{ This attempt to exchange off the powerful bishop lands White in hot water. }
9... Qa5+ 10. c3 b5 { The next few moves are forced: } 11. Nxc5 bxc4 12. Qxd6
Qb5 { The knight on c5 is in danger of being trapped. } 13. a4
{ White has to lash out. } 13... Qb6 14. a5 Nxa5
{ Instead,  14...Qb5  15.Na4  Rd8  16.Qc5  is playable for White. } 15. Qxe5
{ This is a brave move, but it is for the best. } 15... Re8
{ The queen is hounded. } 16. Qd4 Nc6 17. Qe3
{ Necessary. If  17.Qxc4  Ne5  18.Qd4  Qxc5  . } 17... Ng4 18. Na4 Qxe3+ 19.
Bxe3 Nxe3 20. fxe3 Rb8
{ White has managed to survive the early assault, but Black still has the advantage as the knight on a4 is so poorly placed. }
