{ This is too sophisticated. Blocking the king's bishop can't be a good idea. Did no one tell the player of the white pieces that time is of the essence in the opening? By contrast, Black's development is classical and straightforward. }
5... Nf6
{ Threatening the e-pawn. Good start. Black is already ahead in development! }
6. Nbc3
{ White defends the e-pawn and also takes a little control over the d5 square. There is no immediate pressure on Black's position, which allows a choice of where to place the king's bishop. }
6... Bc5
{ 6...Bb4  is also possible, but playing the bishop to c5 is the most dangerous, looking down at one of the weakest squares on the board. I sense tricks. }
