[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. a4
{ A pragmatic move. Black is going to drive away the knight with a6 and often follows up by advancing the pawn to b5. White's a-pawn prevents that advance. }
6... Nf6 7. Bg5
{ This is a curious mix of systems. Basically, it is a Sveshnikov where White has substituted the knight on c3 for the pawn on a4. That gives Black more options than usual. }
7... a6 8. Bxf6
{ This is quite risky! The most sensible continuation for White is  8.N5c3  Be7  9.Bxf6  Bxf6  10.Nd5  O-O  11.Bc4  Bg5  12.O-O  Be6  transposing to a system that is covered in 6.Bc4. }
8... gxf6 9. N5c3 f5
{ This must be the best Sveshnikov I have ever played! Normally White's knight is already on d5. In this version Black has far greater freedom of action. }
10. Bc4
{ The 'normal' moves such as  10.exf5  Bxf5   and  10.Nd5  fxe4  11.Nbc3  Bg7  12.Nxe4  O-O  give Black very easy play: two bishops and a strong pawn centre. }
10... Qg5 11. O-O Be6 12. Nd2 O-O-O
{ Tasty! An option normally unavailable in the Sveshnikov. Black is massing for an attack on the g-file, has two bishops, and a potentially mobile centre. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.a4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. a4
{ A pragmatic move. Black is going to drive away the knight with a6 and often follows up by advancing the pawn to b5. White's a-pawn prevents that advance. }
6... Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3
{ Several standard moves are available to Black at this point, for example,  8...Be7  and  8...Be6  .  But I am going to recommend a finesse that introduces a new tactical possibility. }
8... Bg4
{ Considering that  9.Qd3  and  9.Qd2  both block the bishops, impeding development, then essentially White has two decent moves:  9.Be2  or  9.f3  . }
9. Be2
{ This is a safer move than blocking with f3, but it does allow Black to break out with ...d5. }
9... Bxe2 10. Qxe2 d5
{ The standard pawn break, and it already feels as though Black has the initiative. }
11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 13. O-O
{ Black has several decent continuations:  13...Bxa3  14.Rxa3  O-O  ;  13...Bc5  ;  13...Be7  . In all cases, the position is more comfortable for Black, and that is borne out by the results. Let's follow the most aggressive move, pushing White backwards. }
13... Nd4 14. Qd1 Rd8
{ Supporting the queen means that  15.c3  can be answered by  15...Nb3  . } 15.
Be3 Bc5 16. Bxd4 { White has to give up this bishop in order to develop. }
16... Bxd4 17. Qe2 O-O 18. c3 Bc5 19. Rfd1 Qe6
{ with greater control in the centre, Black has slightly better chances. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.a4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. a4
{ A pragmatic move. Black is going to drive away the knight with a6 and often follows up by advancing the pawn to b5. White's a-pawn prevents that advance. }
6... Nf6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3
{ Several standard moves are available to Black at this point, for example,  8...Be7  and  8...Be6  .  But I am going to recommend a finesse that introduces a new tactical possibility. }
8... Bg4
{ Considering that  9.Qd3  and  9.Qd2  both block the bishops, impeding development, then essentially White has two decent moves:  9.Be2  or  9.f3  . }
9. Be2
{ This is a safer move than blocking with f3, but it does allow Black to break out with ...d5. }
9... Bxe2 10. Qxe2 d5
{ The standard pawn break, and it already feels as though Black has the initiative. }
11. Bg5 dxe4
{ This is the most straightforward way to play: Black will develop speedily. }
12. Nxe4 Qa5+
{ Slipping out of the pin with a check, and perhaps looking to take the pawn on a4. }
13. c3 { Instead,  13.Bd2  Qxa4  is a sound extra pawn for Black. } 13... Nxe4
{ The knight was threatened:  13...Qxa4?  14.Bxf6  would have been catastrophic for Black. }
14. Qxe4 Bxa3
{ Before the knight gets a chance to enter the game on c4, it is eliminated, and White's rook is displaced at the edge of the board. }
15. Rxa3 O-O 16. O-O f5
{ Black goes on the attack with the e and f pawns leading the way - such a common and successful strategy in the Kalashnikov. }
17. Qc4+ Kh8 18. b4 Qc7
{ Black can look forward with confidence as he controls the centre and has a strong attack. }
*

