12. Nb6 Rd8
{ The rook moves to an active square opposite the queen. The pawn break ...d6-d5 gains in power. }
13. Bg5 Be7 14. Bxf6
{ White does best to exchange off bishop for knight, even though the dark squares are now very weak. Instead,  14.Be2  d5!  unleashes fury. }
14... Bxf6 15. Ncd5
{ Instead,  15.Be2  Qc5!  makes it difficult for White to castle. } 15... Bxd5
16. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ The exchange is necessary. Instead  16...Nxc2+  17.Kd2  wins a piece. } 17.
exd5 { Instead  17.Qxd5  Qxc2  wins a pawn. } 17... O-O
{ Black has achieved the typical favourable pawn structure: if White has to recapture on d5 with the pawn, there is no pressure on d6, and there is a healthy kingside pawn majority to push. And don't forget the weak dark squares. }
18. c3 { Otherwise Black busts open the long diagonal with ...e4. } 18... Bg5
{ Because we have induced the pawn move f3, the dark squares are very weak. There is an inviting square for the bishop on e3, and don't forget the f-pawn is ready to fly up the board. Black already has the advantage. }
