10. Bc4 { White wants to castle and challenges the strong bishop on e6. } 10...
Rc8
{ The rook hits the semi-open c-file, the usual place in the Sicilian and particularly good here as we would like to discourage the knight on a3 from returning to a sensible square. There is no need to exchange bishops on c4 - that would only bring the knight on a3 into the game. }
11. O-O Nb4
{ When White plays the pawn to a4, the b4 square becomes available for the knight. This is an important manoeuvre in this variation. The knight puts pressure on the c2 pawn and covers the crucial d5 square. More than that, the rook now attacks the bishop on c4. }
12. Bxe6 fxe6
{ This exchange is usually favourable for Black as the d5 square is covered. Not only can White no longer land a piece there, but the d5 break becomes an option for Black. }
13. f4 Be7 { Black does not fear the endgame. } 14. fxe5 dxe5 15. Qxd8+ Bxd8
{ The bad bishop bounce! } 16. Bd2 Bb6+ 17. Kh1 O-O
{ Black has the better chances because of the more active pieces. The doubled e-pawns are strong: the e6 pawn controls d5 and f5 preventing White from occupying them with a knight. The e5 pawn could provide good support for a knight or bishop. }
