[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Be3
{ According to my database, from a Kalashnikov move-order,  6.Be3  has only been played 386 times: quite a rare occurrence compared to  6.N1c3  @@StartBracket@@10, 148@@EndBracket@@ and  6.c4  @@StartBracket@@5, 882@@EndBracket@@, yet from the Taimanov Sicilian, this is relatively common: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.Nb5  d6  6.Bf4  e5  7.Be3  . Same position, but with an extra move for both sides! In any case, I don't believe this line is troublesome for Black as White often moves the bishop again to g5 and that is time-consuming. Speedy development is of the essence in the opening @@StartBracket@@or at least, it should be!@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nf6 { Instead, } 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 b5
{ Notice that this is a normal Sveshnikov position, except that White's bishop is on e3 rather than g5. That can only help Black. }
9. Nd5 { Black would like to play  9...Nxe4  , but then  10.Bb6  and Nc7+. }
9... Rb8 { The rook covers the b6 square and now ...Nxe4 is threatened. } 10.
Nxf6+
{ Instead,  10.Bg5  Be7  and White is a whole tempo down on a Sveshnikov. In this case 10...Rb8 is the extra move - which is very useful! }
10... Qxf6
{ Quite a few games have reached this position with  11.Be2  and  11.c4  the most popular moves. }
11. Be2
{ Unpretentious development. One could respond in kind with  11...Be7  , ...Be6, ... O-O, with a wholly satisfactory position, but let's be a little bit more ambitious. }
11... Nd4
{ The aim is simple: to gain the bishop pair. The only downside to this move is that kingside development is neglected. But White has also taken liberties and isn't in a position to exploit this foray. }
12. Bxd4
{ Instead,  12.Bg4?  Qg6  is great for Black;   and  12.O-O  Nxe2+  13.Qxe2  Qg6  14.f3  Be7  , followed by O-O and if possible ...f5, is also satisfactory. }
12... exd4 13. O-O g6
{ This gives Black the option to play the bishop to g7 or h6, depending on circumstances. White struggles to find a good plan here for two reasons: the knight needs to be brought back into play and that costs time; if the position opens, Black's bishop pair will fly. }
14. Bd3
{ Blockading the d-pawn is the most prudent, otherwise ...d3 and breaking through on b2 is a permanent option. }
14... Bg7 15. f4
{ Black should not panic about this advance. If the pawn advances to f5, the e5 and e3 squares become available. for Black. The lack of a dark-squared bishop makes itself felt. }
15... O-O 16. Nb1
{ White does best to bring the knight into play. If  16.f5  gxf5  17.exf5  Bh6!  One bishop lands on e3, the other on the long diagonal, and White's kingside gets cut to shreds. }
16... Re8 17. Nd2 Bd7
{ Black's next moves will be to double rooks on the e-file and play the bishop to c6. A tense situation has arisen where White has to take care not to open the position. }
