1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Be3
{ According to my database, from a Kalashnikov move-order,  6.Be3  has only been played 386 times: quite a rare occurrence compared to  6.N1c3  @@StartBracket@@10, 148@@EndBracket@@ and  6.c4  @@StartBracket@@5, 882@@EndBracket@@, yet from the Taimanov Sicilian, this is relatively common: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.Nb5  d6  6.Bf4  e5  7.Be3  . Same position, but with an extra move for both sides! In any case, I don't believe this line is troublesome for Black as White often moves the bishop again to g5 and that is time-consuming. Speedy development is of the essence in the opening @@StartBracket@@or at least, it should be!@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nf6 { Threatening the e-pawn! } 7. Bg5 Be6 8. c4
{ I find the combination of c4 and Bg5 odd. If White is going to exchange the bishop for the knight on f6, then there is a massive gaping hole ready for Black's knight to leap into. }
8... Be7 { There is no need to push the knight yet. } 9. N1c3
{ It is wise for White to avoid the exchange on f6. But that does mean that the foray with the bishop to g5 was ineffective. }
9... O-O 10. Be2 a6 11. Na3
{ We are following a game between Leko-Grischuk, Beijing 2013. In this position the Russian exploited a typical tactical weakness of the bishop on g5. }
11... Nxe4 12. Bxe7
{ White is in trouble. Instead,  12.Nxe4  Bxg5  13.Nxd6  Qa5+  , followed by ...Rfd8 wins for Black. Or  13.Qxd6  Qa5+  14.Kf1  Be7  15.Qd2  Bb4  gives Black a tremendous initiative. }
12... Nxc3 13. Bxd8 Nxd1 14. Bc7 Nxb2 15. Bxd6 Rfd8 16. c5 Na4
{ With a clear extra pawn for Black, Leko-Grischuk, Beijing 2013. } *

