1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Be3
{ According to my database, from a Kalashnikov move-order,  6.Be3  has only been played 386 times: quite a rare occurrence compared to  6.N1c3  @@StartBracket@@10, 148@@EndBracket@@ and  6.c4  @@StartBracket@@5, 882@@EndBracket@@, yet from the Taimanov Sicilian, this is relatively common: @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  e6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nc6  5.Nb5  d6  6.Bf4  e5  7.Be3  . Same position, but with an extra move for both sides! In any case, I don't believe this line is troublesome for Black as White often moves the bishop again to g5 and that is time-consuming. Speedy development is of the essence in the opening @@StartBracket@@or at least, it should be!@@EndBracket@@. }
6... Nf6 { Threatening the e-pawn! } 7. Bg5 Be6 8. Bxf6
{ White breaks up Black's pawns, but do not fear! Those centre pawns are a great asset and don't forget those fantastic bishops too. }
8... gxf6 9. Nd2 a6 10. Nc3 f5
{ Comparing this with similar Sveshnikov positions, White's pieces are more modestly placed and Black hasn't compromised the queenside pawns. }
11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Nd5 Bg7 { Don't those bishops look good? } 13. Nc4 O-O 14. c3
Be6
{ The bishop pre-empts an attack with  Ne3  , challenges the knight, and makes way for the f-pawn. Strangely, if instead  14...b5  15.Nce3  Be6  there is a transposition to a line of the Sveshnikov where hundreds of games have been played @@StartBracket@@and it also has a good reputation for Black!@@EndBracket@@. However, I see no reason to push White's knight to a better square. }
15. Ncb6 Rb8 16. Bc4 e4
{ Making room for the knight to move to  e5  . Instead,  16...f5  17.Ne3  allows Black to exchange bishops and puts pressure on the d6 pawn. }
17. O-O Ne5 { That knight has range, looking all over the board. } 18. Bb3 Qh4
{ Black has the makings of a strong attack on the kingside. } *

