6... Nf6 { Threatening the e-pawn! } 7. Bg5 Be6 8. Nd2
{ This is the main idea of the variation: instead of playing the knight to c3 which means that the knight on b5 has to retreat to the poor square on a3, the knight moves to d2, leaving the c3 square free. Very neat, but considering the number of knight moves White has made, not to mention Bc1-e3-g5, this is hardly the most efficient method of development.   Just by way of comparison, if instead  8.N1c3  a6  9.Na3  b5  10.Nd5  , White is a whole tempo down on a normal Sveshnikov position @@StartBracket@@Black's bishop on  e6  is the extra move@@EndBracket@@. }
8... Be7 9. Bxf6
{ If White does not exchange, Black has a very easy game. For example,  9.Bc4  d5  equalises immediately. }
9... Bxf6 10. Nc4
{ This has been a fairly popular line @@StartBracket@@in my database there are around 30 games that reached this position@@EndBracket@@. The d-pawn is doomed, but count how many knight moves White has made to reach this position - five. That is out of balance with the natural laws of the game and Black, with a lead in development and two beautiful bishops can gain excellent compensation. In fact, given the risks that White is undertaking, it's a mystery to me why this has been so popular. }
10... O-O { Black's king is safe - unlike its counterpart. } 11. Qxd6
{ Instead,  11.Nbxd6  Qe7  @@StartBracket@@threatening ...Rd8@@EndBracket@@  12.Nf5  Bxf5  13.exf5  Rad8  14.Qg4  e4  , with the idea ...Qb4+ @@StartBracket@@among others@@EndBracket@@ is good for Black.   And  11.Ncxd6  Qb6  is even worse. }
11... Qc8
{ This is the most dangerous way to play, stepping aside so that the rook can come to d8 to attack the queen. White must already take great care if he is to emerge unscathed from the opening. }
12. c3
{ This is necessary. Instead, if White plays a 'normal' developing move such as  12.Bd3  , then  12...Bxc4  13.Bxc4  a6  14.Na3  Rd8  15.Qc5  Be7  16.Qe3  Nd4  gives Black a dangerous initiative. }
12... Rd8
{ 12...Be7  has also been played here, and the lines often transpose. Playing the rook to d8 gives White fewer options as the queen should move to c7. }
13. Qc7 Be7
{ Playing the bishop back appears odd, but it blocks the seventh rank and prepares to exchange on c4. }
14. Be2 { This is a mistake. } 14... Bxc4 15. Bxc4 a6
{ In this case, everything works for Black because the seventh rank is blocked, so White cannot capture on f7. }
16. Qxc8 Raxc8 17. Na3 Bxa3 { 17...Nd4  is also promising. } 18. bxa3 Nd4 19.
Bxf7+ { Instead,  19.cxd4  Rxc4  is even worse for White. } 19... Kxf7 20. cxd4
Rxd4 21. O-O Rxe4
{ The active rooks give Black a clear advantage in the endgame. } *

