12. c3
{ This is necessary. Instead, if White plays a 'normal' developing move such as  12.Bd3  , then  12...Bxc4  13.Bxc4  a6  14.Na3  Rd8  15.Qc5  Be7  16.Qe3  Nd4  gives Black a dangerous initiative. }
12... Rd8
{ 12...Be7  has also been played here, and the lines often transpose. Playing the rook to d8 gives White fewer options as the queen should move to c7. }
13. Qc7 Be7
{ Playing the bishop back appears odd, but it blocks the seventh rank and prepares to exchange on c4. }
14. Qxc8
{ This is a prudent choice. White needs to reduce the danger. Having said that, even without queens, the situation is perilous. }
14... Raxc8 15. Nba3
{ Retreating isn't very desirable, particularly when White hasn't yet developed, but this is necessary.   Instead,  15.Ne3  a6  16.Na3  Bxa3  17.bxa3  Na5  regains the pawn with interest. }
15... Nb8
{ A remarkably cool move, and I must admit, this is a computer suggestion.   Instead, the more straightforward  15...Nd4  has been played, which certainly presents White with some difficult questions to answer. However, with best play, White should survive @@StartBracket@@I'll leave that to you to investigate on your own!@@EndBracket@@. }
16. Be2
{ Finally, White starts to develop the kingside.   Instead  16.Nxe5  Bxa3  17.bxa3  Rxc3  and Black will get his pawn back @@StartBracket@@at least@@EndBracket@@. }
