1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Bc4
{ A classical move. The diagonal is open and the bishop occupies it. } 6... a6
{ Pushing the knight back immediately creates a traffic jam. White's pieces tread on each other's toes. }
7. N5c3 Nf6 8. Bg5
{ White needs to occupy the d5 square with the knight to unblock the minor pieces. To do that the knight on f6 will be exchanged off. }
8... Be7 { The bishop develops and Black prepares to castle. All as normal. }
9. Bxf6
{ White could castle first, but this is the most consistent, looking to occupy d5 immediately. In fact, after  9.O-O  O-O  10.Bxf6  we would transpose to our mainline. }
9... Bxf6 10. Nd5 O-O 11. a3
{ Castling would transpose into our mainline, but Nigel Short once played this plan of tucking away the bishop on a2. }
11... Bg5
{ The bishop cannot be challenged on this diagonal, so this is a powerful piece. }
12. O-O Be6 { Starting the process of challenging the knight on d5. } 13. Nd2
Rc8
{ The rook moves to the semi-open file which practically forces the bishop back to the side of the board. }
14. Ba2 Kh8
{ In the game Short-Ivanchuk, Monte Carlo 1993, Black played  14...Bxd2  15.Qxd2  Ne7  16.c3  Bxd5  17.Bxd5  Nxd5  18.Qxd5  Qb6  , which is a level position. A very responsible way of playing, but Black can play more ambitiously. }
15. c3 g6
{ Preparing to advance the f-pawn. We want to have the option of recapturing with the g-pawn. }
16. Nf3 Bh6
{ That's an important piece, we should remove it from the range of the knight. }
17. Re1 f5
{ Black has pressure on the centre and potential to attack on the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.Bc4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Bc4
{ A classical move. The diagonal is open and the bishop occupies it. } 6... a6
{ Pushing the knight back immediately creates a traffic jam. White's pieces tread on each other's toes. }
7. N5c3 Nf6 8. Bg5
{ White needs to occupy the d5 square with the knight to unblock the minor pieces. To do that the knight on f6 will be exchanged off. }
8... Be7 { The bishop develops and Black prepares to castle. All as normal. }
9. Bxf6
{ White could castle first, but this is the most consistent, looking to occupy d5 immediately. In fact, after  9.O-O  O-O  10.Bxf6  we would transpose to our mainline. }
9... Bxf6 10. O-O
{ Move order here is flexible. I am going to take  10.O-O  as the main move, but naturally White could play  10.Nd5  first. In the vast majority of cases, a transposition occurs as White has to castle kingside. }
10... O-O 11. Nd5 Bg5
{ This is the starting position of the variation. Although White has firm control over the d5 square, the problem is that it is too firm! The knight on d5 actually blocks the other two minor pieces. Black's bishop on g5 plays a key role in this position: it is unopposed and controls key squares in the heart of White's position. }
12. a4
{ Preventing expansion with ...b5 and preparing a home for the bishop on a2. }
12... Be6
{ Sound development, putting pressure on the knight and preparing ...Rc8. } 13.
Nbc3 Rc8
{ Rooks belong on open files @@StartBracket@@and semi-open files, but that's less catchy@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Ba2 { The bishop moves away from the rook. } 14... Kh8
{ The first step in preparing to advance the f-pawn. The king moves away from the beam of the bishop on a2, avoiding tactics. }
15. Qd3 Bh6
{ This preempts White's f-pawn advance and gives Black's queen a route to the kingside. }
16. Rad1 g6
{ This supports the f-pawn  @@StartBracket@@recapturing on f5 with the g-pawn preserves a strong centre@@EndBracket@@. }
17. Ne2 { Preventing Black's knight from leaping into d4. } 17... Qh4
{ The queen is an irritant for White. There is a bit of pressure on the e4 and f2 pawns and attacking the queen with g3 weakens the kingside. The pawn advance f5 is finally ready, with good counterplay. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.Bc4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Bc4
{ A classical move. The diagonal is open and the bishop occupies it. } 6... a6
{ Pushing the knight back immediately creates a traffic jam. White's pieces tread on each other's toes. }
7. N5c3 Nf6 8. Bg5
{ White needs to occupy the d5 square with the knight to unblock the minor pieces. To do that the knight on f6 will be exchanged off. }
8... Be7 { The bishop develops and Black prepares to castle. All as normal. }
9. Bxf6
{ White could castle first, but this is the most consistent, looking to occupy d5 immediately. In fact, after  9.O-O  O-O  10.Bxf6  we would transpose to our mainline. }
9... Bxf6 10. O-O
{ Move order here is flexible. I am going to take  10. 0-0 as the main move, but naturally White could play  10.Nd5  first. In the vast majority of cases, a transposition occurs as White has to castle kingside. }
10... O-O 11. Nd5 Bg5
{ This is the starting position of the variation. Although White has firm control over the d5 square, the problem is that it is too firm! The knight on d5 actually blocks the other two minor pieces. Black's bishop on g5 plays a key role in this position: it is unopposed and controls key squares in the heart of White's position. }
12. Nbc3 b5
{ White has carelessly allowed Black to expand on the queenside. This is classic Sicilian play, beginning an attack on the c-file. }
13. Bb3 Be6 { We shouldn't forget our development. } 14. Qd3 Rc8
{ Play starts on the c-file. } 15. Rad1 Na5
{ The knight has the option to exchange on b3 or hop into c4 with excellent counterplay. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.N5c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N5c3
{ White aims to get the knight to d5, but in so doing creates a mini traffic jam. }
6... Nf6
{ A normal developing move but in this position, it prevents White from playing  7.Nd5?  because of  7...Nxe4  . Therefore @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  is necessary. }
7. Bg5 Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing to castle. } 8. Bxf6
{ Instead  8.Bc4  O-O  9.Bxf6  Bxf6  10.Nd5  will transpose to the mainline. }
8... Bxf6 9. Nd5
{ White carries through the plan of establishing the knight on d5 and clears the blockage of pieces on the queenside. }
9... O-O 10. Nbc3 Be6
{ This move order is precise. I instinctively want to move the bishop to g5, but playing it there before White has castled invites pawn to h4. We are also setting a trap for White: want to grab a pawn? White has to decide how to develop the king's bishop. Moving to d3 blocks the d-file. Moving to e2 is in range of the knight moving to d4.  11.g3  and Bg2, as well as  11.Bc4  , are the most plausible. }
11. g3 Nd4
{ The knight covers the d-file and starts to target the c2 square. Black can take the initiative as White is still concerned with development. }
12. Bg2 Rc8 { The c3 knight is nailed to its spot. } 13. O-O Bxd5 14. exd5
{ This is the pawn structure that we want to see when playing with Black: the pressure is off the pawn on d6 and White can no longer use the d5 outpost for a piece.   White is unable to recapture with the knight because the c2 pawn hangs  14.Nxd5  Rxc2  . }
14... g6
{ Black already has the better chances. The bishop steps safely back to g7, and then Black has a choice whether to pursue an attack on the kingside with ...f5 or on the queenside with ...b5. }
