1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N5c3
{ White aims to get the knight to d5, but in so doing creates a mini traffic jam. }
6... Nf6
{ A normal developing move but in this position, it prevents White from playing  7.Nd5?  because of  7...Nxe4  . Therefore @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/pp3ppp/2np1n2/4p3/4P3/2N5/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  is necessary. }
7. Bg5 Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing to castle. } 8. Bxf6
{ Instead  8.Bc4  O-O  9.Bxf6  Bxf6  10.Nd5  will transpose to the mainline. }
8... Bxf6 9. Nd5
{ White carries through the plan of establishing the knight on d5 and clears the blockage of pieces on the queenside. }
9... O-O 10. Nbc3 Be6
{ This move order is precise. I instinctively want to move the bishop to g5, but playing it there before White has castled invites pawn to h4. We are also setting a trap for White: want to grab a pawn?  White has to decide how to develop the king's bishop. Moving to d3 blocks the d-file.   Moving to e2 is in range of the knight moving to d4.  11.g3  and Bg2, as well as  11.Bc4  , are the most plausible. }
11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. Qxd6
{ As is so often the case, this early snaffle is perilous. } 12... Rfd8
{ Hit! } 13. Qc5 Nd4 { Hit! } 14. Bd3
{ Instead  14.Rc1  Qf4  already wins for Black! } 14... b6 15. Qb4 Qg5
{ Black has several strong moves, but this is the most direct. } 16. Kf1
{ An unpleasant move to have to make, but actually the best. Just because of the displaced king, Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn.   If  16.O-O  Nf3+  17.Kh1  Qf4  forces checkmate.   Or  16.g3  Nf3+  17.Ke2  Rxd3  18.cxd3  Nd4+  wins.   And  16.h4  Nxc2+  17.Bxc2  Qd2+  18.Kf1  Qxc2  gives Black a winning initiative. }
16... Rac8
{ Breaking free from this position is very difficult for White: the queen is out of play, the rooks are split, and the king is vulnerable. For example, if  17.h4  Qf6  18.Kg1  Nxc2  19.Bxc2  Rd2  , Black wins back the piece with a huge advantage. }
