7. Bg5 Be7 { Breaking the pin and preparing to castle. } 8. Bxf6
{ Instead  8.Bc4  O-O  9.Bxf6  Bxf6  10.Nd5  will transpose to the mainline. }
8... Bxf6 9. Nd5
{ White carries through the plan of establishing the knight on d5 and clears the blockage of pieces on the queenside. }
9... O-O 10. Nbc3 Be6
{ This move order is precise. I instinctively want to move the bishop to g5, but playing it there before White has castled invites pawn to h4. We are also setting a trap for White: want to grab a pawn? White has to decide how to develop the king's bishop. Moving to d3 blocks the d-file. Moving to e2 is in range of the knight moving to d4.  11.g3  and Bg2, as well as  11.Bc4  , are the most plausible. }
11. Bc4 Rc8 { Aiming at the bishop and setting up pressure on the c-file. } 12.
O-O a6
{ Threatening to expand on the queenside. White should close down that possibility. }
13. a4 Bg5
{ This position can also be reached via the 6. Bc4 variation and I am going to remain consistent and recommend exactly the same! }
14. Ba2 Kh8
{ The first step in preparing to advance the f-pawn. The king moves away from the beam of the bishop on a2, avoiding tactics. }
15. Qd3 Bh6
{ This preempts White's f-pawn advance and gives Black's queen a route to the kingside. }
16. Rad1 g6
{ This supports the f-pawn  @@StartBracket@@recapturing on f5 with the g-pawn preserves a strong centre@@EndBracket@@. }
17. Ne2 { Preventing Black's knight from leaping into d4. } 17... Qh4
{ The queen is an irritant for White. There is a bit of pressure on the e4 and f2 pawns and attacking the queen with g3 weakens the kingside. The pawn advance f5 is finally ready, with good counterplay. }
