[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. g3
{ A gentle continuation. Whether the bishop is well placed on g2 is debatable. But one thing is certain: to get it there takes a pawn move, and that slows down White's development. Combined with the errant knight on b5, it feels as though too many liberties are being taken. Black has a wide choice of options, but I favour one that tries to exploit White's lag in development. }
6... Be7 { This comes first. Instead,  6...Nf6  7.Bg5  is a bit annoying. } 7.
Bg2 Nf6
{ Standard development. The knight is on its best square fighting for control over e4 and d5. }
8. h3
{ Preventing ...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@see the mainline@@EndBracket@@. A tidy move, but another pawn move, meaning that White falls a little further behind in development. Black can use the time to expand on the queenside. }
8... a6 9. N5c3 b5
{ This expansion feels appropriate considering that White has consumed so much time @@StartBracket@@g3, Bg2, h3@@EndBracket@@, and also that the king's bishop no longer stands on the f1-a6 diagonal. }
10. O-O O-O 11. Be3
{ The bishop can develop to this stable square as ...Ng4 is no longer possible. }
11... Na5
{ We can see how the absence of the bishop on the f1-a6 diagonal allows Black to generate counterplay on the queenside. }
12. Nd2 { Covering the c4 square. } 12... Bb7
{ Putting pressure on e4 and covering the d5 square. } 13. a3
{ Instead,  13.Nd5  Nxd5  14.exd5  f5  and White is coming under pressure all over the board. }
13... Rc8 14. Qe2 d5
{ White has been so slow with development that Black achieves this break with ease. }
15. exd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. c3 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 f5
{ Black carries his opening initiative into the middlegame, flexing the kingside pawn majority. }
