1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. g3
{ A gentle continuation. Whether the bishop is well placed on g2 is debatable. But one thing is certain: to get it there takes a pawn move, and that slows down White's development. Combined with the errant knight on b5, it feels as though too many liberties are being taken. Black has a wide choice of options, but I favour one that tries to exploit White's lag in development. }
6... Be7 { This comes first. Instead,  6...Nf6  7.Bg5  is a bit annoying. } 7.
Bg2 Nf6
{ Standard development. The knight is on its best square fighting for control over e4 and d5. }
8. O-O Bg4
{ By the way, let's rule out  9.Bf3  . Black responds with  9...h5  and White is already struggling with a weak kingside and a weak e-pawn. }
9. Qd3
{ If White develops successfully, then the queen will be reasonably placed, but in the meantime, Black can exploit its vulnerable position. }
9... Rc8
{ The rook belongs on the c-file, and in this case, it gets there with a gain of time as ...Nb4 is threatened. }
10. c4
{ This is risky. Not only will Black be able to sink the knight into d4, but the c4 pawn is also vulnerable. }
10... a6 11. N5a3
{ The knight has to retreat to this poor square. Instead  11.N5c3?  Nb4  12.Qd2  Rxc4  wins a pawn. }
11... Nd4 { A tricky move. White has to take great care. } 12. Re1 h5
{ Black could play more conventionally with ...Nd7, but the h-pawn advance is more testing. }
13. Be3 h4 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. Qxd4 Qa5 16. Nc3 hxg3 17. hxg3 Qh5
{ with the attack! } *

