1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Be2
{ A modest response to Black's opening and one that does not cause difficulties. }
6... Nf6
{ I prefer this to  6...Be7  as White would still have the option to play  7.c4  transposing to the Maroczy bind - but as you will see from my repertoire, I would like the bishop to move to g7 against that set-up. }
7. N5c3
{ The fourth move with this knight. On general principles, White's play cannot be recommended. }
7... Be7 8. Bg5
{ White wants to take on f6 and play the knight into d5 @@StartBracket@@we will see this idea in one of the later lines@@EndBracket@@. Black could fall in with that by playing  8...O-O  9.Bxf6  Bxf6  10.Nd5  Be6  , which is fine. But at this moment there is a chance to cut across White's plan. Whether you do this is perhaps a question of taste. }
8... Nxe4
{ A standard tactic when the bishop is on g5. Naturally, in each case, the consequences of this strike need to calculated carefully, but let me save you the time: this results in a position where Black is very comfortable. }
9. Nxe4
{ Instead  9.Bxe7  Nxc3  10.Bxd8  Nxd1  11.Bc7  Nxb2  12.Bxd6  Be6  leaves Black a safe pawn up. }
9... Bxg5 10. Nxd6+ Ke7
{ White recovers the pawn, but the knight cannot be maintained on the d6 square. }
11. Nxc8+ { It is best for White to simplify. } 11... Rxc8 12. Nc3 Qxd1+
{ Given that Black's king is in the middle of the board, exchanging queens is the best policy. }
13. Rxd1 Rhd8
{ With the extra centre pawn on e5, Black looks better, but with a few precise moves White should equalise. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.Be2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Be2
{ A modest response to Black's opening and one that does not cause difficulties. }
6... Nf6
{ I prefer this to  6...Be7  as White would still have the option to play  7.c4  transposing to the Maroczy bind - but as you will see from my repertoire, I would like the bishop to move to g7 against that set-up. }
7. Bg5 a6 8. N5c3
{ This leads the game back into fairly standard Kalashnikov positions where White's bishop stands modestly on e2. }
8... Be7 9. Bxf6
{ White continues logically, eliminating the knight and enabling the knight on c3 to move forward, which in turn gives more space to manoeuvre. White could also play  9.O-O  first, to which Black would answer  9...O-O  , and then White has nothing better than to exchange on f6, transposing to our mainline here. }
9... Bxf6 10. Nd5 Be6
{ By playing the bishop to  e6  immediately, Black discourages White from playing  11.Nd2  . In that case, Black could play  11...Bxd5  12.exd5  Ne7  achieving a favourable pawn structure. }
11. O-O
{ Instead, grabbing the pawn would be a mistake:  11.Nxf6+  Qxf6  12.Qxd6  Qg5  13.O-O  Nd4  14.Nc3  Bh3  , winning material. }
11... O-O
{ We can still tempt White into taking that pawn on  d6  , and it is still a mistake to take:  12.Nxf6+  Qxf6  13.Qxd6  Rfd8  14.Qa3  Nd4  with a wonderful initiative. Here, it looks obvious that White is suffering, but in such situations so many players get greedy! }
12. c3 { preventing the knight from hopping into d4. } 12... Bg5
{ The bishop finds a fine vista. } 13. Na3 b5
{ This leads into a variation of the Sveshnikov which is perfectly satisfactory for Black. Why the change in strategy? Why advance the b-pawn at this stage?  13...Ne7  is also possible, but that would encourage the bishop to move to c4, giving White's pieces a little more freedom. }
14. Nc2
{ My database shows that well over one hundred serious classical games have arrived at this position, mainly through a Sveshnikov move order. Do not fear that you are getting embroiled in an intense and intricate theoretical debate. Without going into too many details, this line is fine for Black as ...Rb8 has not been included, so the central point on d5 can be contested immediately. }
14... Ne7
{ This is by far the best strategy. Don't push the f-pawn! That will not lead to an attack on White's king, the opposite in fact: in the long term, Black's kingside is damaged. }
15. Ncb4
{ Instead,  15.Nxe7+  Qxe7  16.Nb4  a5  17.Nd5  Qb7  leads to the same position.   Or  15.Nce3  Bxe3  16.Nxe3  d5  and Black liberates. }
15... a5 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Nd5 Qb7
{ With this move, increasing the pressure on the d5 square, Black ensures that the knight will be exchanged, leaving a pawn on d5. }
18. Qd3 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. exd5 Rab8
{ We have been following the game Dervishi-Krasenkov, Ohrid 2001. Black has achieved a favourable pawn structure: White cannot exploit the queenside majority, but Black's kingside majority is mobile and dangerous. As the opposite-coloured bishops cannot be exchanged, Black has a long-term initiative. 0-1 @@StartBracket@@97@@EndBracket@@ Dervishi,E @@StartBracket@@2491@@EndBracket@@-Krasenkow,M @@StartBracket@@2655@@EndBracket@@ Ohrid 2001 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.Be2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Be2
{ A modest response to Black's opening and one that does not cause difficulties. }
6... Nf6
{ I prefer this to  6...Be7  as White would still have the option to play  7.c4  transposing to the Maroczy bind - but as you will see from my repertoire, I would like the bishop to move to g7 against that set-up. }
7. Bg5 a6 8. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Black is forced to recapture with the g-pawn, but this results in an excellent type of Sveshnikov variation where White's centre comes under immediate pressure, only without the compensating piece activity. }
9. N5c3 f5
{ The key move. Knocking out the e-pawn will allow the second f-pawn to advance. }
10. O-O Bg7
{ Black wants to castle, exchange pawns on e4 and then either advance ...d5 or ...f5. }
11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Nd5 O-O 13. c3 Be6
{ This is the kind of position that can arise from the Sveshnikov variation, but with a couple of differences that favour Black. First, White is behind in development, and that helps Black when he is attacking the centre. Second, the b-pawn remains on b7, depriving White of a source of counterplay @@StartBracket@@in the Sveshnikov, the pawn on b5 is often attacked by pawn to a4@@EndBracket@@.   Black has two bishops and a strong pawn centre, and White is therefore struggling to equalise! }
14. Na3 Ne7 { White struggles to hold on to the pivotal d5 square. } 15. Bf3
{ Instead, if  15.Nxe7+  Qxe7  16.Bc4  Rac8!  17.Bd5  Rc5!  @@StartBracket@@A typical manoeuvre fighting for control over d5@@EndBracket@@  18.Bxe6  Qxe6  . Black is ready to push either d or f-pawn and has a clear positional advantage. }
15... Rc8 16. Nc2 Rc5
{ This manoeuvre again. Black is ready to follow up with pawn to f5 and shake White's central control. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Bg5
{ This looks terrible - and it is terrible. Take it! } 6... Qxg5 7. Nc7+ Kd8 8.
Nxa8
{ For the moment, White is the exchange up, but that knight in the corner is trapped, and then the material balance will tip the other way. Besides, Black already has a lead in development and that isn't easy for White to manage. }
8... Nf6 { Black develops with a gain of tempo. } 9. Nc3 Nd4
{ There is no need to win the knight on a8 straightaway. First, let's make it as difficult as possible for White to develop. White must already tread carefully to avoid losing on the spot. }
10. Qd3 d5 { Very bold! White is under massive pressure. } 11. exd5
{ Instead,  11.Nxd5  Nxd5  12.exd5  Bf5  and ...Nxc2+ wins for Black. } 11...
Bf5 { That's the point. Black is breaking through to the king. } 12. Qc4 Nxc2+
13. Kd1 Qg4+
{ Black could play  13...Bd6  @@StartBracket@@with a winning position@@EndBracket@@, but exchanging queens is a practical choice: less can go wrong. }
14. Kd2 Qxc4 15. Bxc4 Nxa1
{ Taking the rook is also a good practical choice :@@EndBracket@@ } 16. Rxa1
Bd6
{ The king will move to e7 and then rook takes knight. Black has an extra piece. }
