[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Kalashnikov 5.Nb5 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashikov 5.Nb5 d6 6.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. Bg5
{ This looks terrible - and it is terrible. Take it! } 6... Qxg5 7. Nc7+ Kd8 8.
Nxa8
{ For the moment, White is the exchange up, but that knight in the corner is trapped, and then the material balance will tip the other way. Besides, Black already has a lead in development and that isn't easy for White to manage. }
8... Nf6 { Black develops with a gain of tempo. } 9. Nc3 Nd4
{ There is no need to win the knight on a8 straightaway. First, let's make it as difficult as possible for White to develop. White must already tread carefully to avoid losing on the spot. }
10. h4 { A vain attempt to drive away the queen. } 10... Qf4
{ The queen remains active, attacking the e-pawn. } 11. Bd3 Be6
{ There is no need for Black to rush: simple development will suffice. The threat is to play ...Be7, ...Kd7, and ... Rxa8 when Black will have a material advantage - as well as the attack. White cannot do much to cross this. }
12. a4 { If  12.g3  Qg4  and Black remains in control. } 12... Be7 13. Nb5
{ An attempt to rescue the stranded knight - which fails miserably. } 13...
Nxe4 { Threatening the pawn on f2. } 14. O-O
{ Out of the frying pan and into the fire. The f2 square has been defended and immediate danger averted, but the king faces a lethal assault in its new location. }
14... Bg4 15. f3 Qe3+ 16. Kh2 Bxh4 17. Bxe4 Qh6
{ I'll allow you to analyse the details of this position yourself, but suffice to say that Black has a winning attack. }
