9. Nxe7
{ Is it such a big deal if White takes the bishop? No. Black's development accelerates and in general it looks odd for White to exchange off a piece that has made so many moves. A glance at the board tells us that Black has more pieces in play than White. }
9... Nxe7
{ Recapturing with the queen is also fine, but this has done slightly better in practice. }
10. Bd3 d5
{ With this standard pawn break, Black gains control of the centre.   Incidentally Magnus Carlsen once played  10...O-O  here, which is also fine. }
11. exd5 Nexd5 12. O-O O-O
{ The pawn on e5 gives Black a greater share of the centre and easy development. }
13. Bg5 { The pin doesn't help White: } 13... h6 14. Bh4 Nf4
{ Black already had a pleasant initiative in the game Warakomska-Sadzikowski, London 2016. The knight can be supported with ... g5 and Black has easy development with the bishop moving to e6. }
