{ The position is tricky for White. Black just wants to move the queen and put a rook on d8. }
12. c3 Qc7
{ Instead,  12...b5  would transpose to the main line and is quite playable, but moving the queen away directly is even more dangerous. White has to tread carefully. }
13. Nc4 Rfd8 14. Qc2 b5 15. Ne3 Rac8
{ Over the last few moves Black has brought his pieces into play and at the same time attacked White's pieces. He has a significant lead in development. }
16. Be2 Qa5 17. Bd2 Bg5
{ So often the right square for the bishop in the Kalashnikov. The pressure increases. }
18. O-O b4
{ Black has a strong initiative, though White can hold the position with accurate play. }
