14. Ne3 { This is the only move that gives White a route to safety. } 14...
Rfd8 15. Nd5
{ This is the most prudent choice, returning the pawn in order to bring the king to safety.   15.Qc2  is asking for trouble. The best reply is  15...Rac8  and something nasty is about to happen involving ...Nd4 or ...b4, depending on White's response.   15.Bd2  self-pinning is risky. Black has good compensation for the pawn after any of these moves:  15...Rd6  ,  15...Bg5  or  15...Qc7 }
15... Bxd5 { With this Black regains the pawn } 16. exd5 Ne7 17. Qc2
{ The queen steps out of the way of the rook. } 17... Nxd5 18. Bd3 g6
{ Blocking out the bishop.   If one wanted to be adventurous @@StartBracket@@and also take a risk@@EndBracket@@ then  18...b4  is possible. }
19. O-O Rac8
{ The position is roughly level. Black will probably play for ...b4 to force c4 so that the d4 square can be occupied by the knight spinning round via e7 and c6. }
