{ White has already spent four turns moving his king's knight and leaves it on the poor a3 square. Time is of the essence - so why make another pawn move? This is not to be recommended. }
8... Nf6 9. Bg2 Bg4
{ The bishop causes serious disruption in White's camp.   Instead, Carlsen played  9...b5  in a rapid-play game against Nepomniachtchi @@StartBracket@@and won brilliantly@@EndBracket@@ but this is stronger. }
10. Qd2 Nd4 { Threatens ...Nf3+. } 11. O-O Rc8
{ Preventing the knight on a3 from returning to play. } 12. f3 Bd7
{ The bishop has been driven back, but White's position is still a bit of a mess: how is the knight on a3 going to come back into play? }
*

