[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9. Kalashnikov 6.N1c3 - 8.Nc4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 6.N1c3 - 8.Nc4 b5 9.Ne3 Nf6 10.Ned5 #11"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ That already looks pleasant from Black's viewpoint. The knight has been sent back to a poor square. Much of the subsequent opening and middlegame struggle will centre on whether that knight can transfer to a decent square. }
7... Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nc4 { Redeploying the wayward knight is the best policy. } 8... b5
{ Forcing the knight to move again. This is overwhelmingly the most popular move.   Instead  8...Nf6  runs into  9.Bg5  with the threat to take on  f6  . }
9. Ne3
{ From White's viewpoint, the position has improved because the errant knight on a3 has succeeded in finding a better home on e3. But Black can also be content: the knight manoeuvres have cost White much time. }
9... Nf6
{ This is the starting point of the mainline of the 7...Be7 variation. From here there are four main moves:  10.a3  ,  10.Ned5  ,  10.Bd3  and the most popular,  10.g3  . }
10. Ned5
{ The seventh move with this knight in the first ten moves! Considering that Black has done nothing wrong and has continued developing sensibly, the position MUST be fine for the good guys. }
10... O-O
{ Black's king is already safe while White's is still in the middle. That provides tasty opportunities to attack! White has quite a few options at this point, although most lead to typically generic Kalashnikov middlegame positions. }
11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Nd5
{ White has achieved the goal of planting the knight on d5, but only by neglecting development. Besides, the knight can be challenged very easily by playing ...Be6 and ...Ne7. In short, I'm not impressed by White's manoeuvrings! }
12... Be6 13. c3
{ The most prudent move, cutting out the knight from the d4 square. } 13... Bg5
{ The standard Kalashnikov manoeuvre to improve the position of the bishop. }
14. Be2 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Ne7
{ Black continues the battle for the d5 square. White cannot keep control. }
16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. O-O Rfd8
{ with the intention of playing ...d5. Black's strategy of contesting the d5 square has worked well and he is already calling the shots. Molano Lafuente-Ikonnikov, Barcelona 2009. I have included this in the 'Model Games' chapter. }
*

