11... Nb4
{ Exchanging off the light-squared bishop is desirable for Black: key squares in this position are d5, f5, e4, and c2 - all on light squares. Once the bishop is gone, the fight tips towards Black. }
12. Be2 { The best move: in principle White needs to retain that bishop. }
12... Be6 13. a3 Nc6 14. Bd3 Nd7
{ A common and effective manoeuvre in the Kalashnikov: the knight makes room for the bishop to emerge on g5, and the knight may return to f6 to continue the fight for the d5 square, or swing round to b6 or c5. }
15. Ncd5 Bg5
{ The pressure grows on e3 and d5. Notice how it is Black who decides when to exchange. }
16. c3 Ne7
{ Black continues the fight for the d5 square. The aim is to exchange so that White ends up with a pawn on d5 giving Black his favoured kingside pawn majority. }
17. Bc2
{ The queen covers the d5 square. Black has a wide choice of plans here. One can exchange on e3 or d5, but it seems to me that Black can happily wait and improve the position of the queen's rook. }
17... Rc8 { with chances for both sides. } *

