13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bg2
{ In this case, Black can take the initiative by hounding the bishop. } 14...
h3 15. Bf3 Nd4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Kalashnikov 6.N1c3 - 8.Nc4 Mainline with 10.g3 h5"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 6.N1c3 - 8.Nc4 Main Line with 10.g3 h5 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ That already looks pleasant from Black's viewpoint. The knight has been sent back to a poor square. Much of the subsequent opening and middlegame struggle will centre on whether that knight can transfer to a decent square. }
7... Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nc4 b5
{ Forcing the knight to move again. This is overwhelmingly the most popular move.   Instead  8...Nf6  runs into  9.Bg5  with the threat to take on  f6  . }
9. Ne3
{ From White's viewpoint, the position has improved because the errant knight on a3 has succeeded in finding a better home on e3. But Black can also be content: the knight manoeuvres have cost White much time. }
9... Nf6
{ This is the starting point of the mainline of the 7...Be7 variation. From here there are four main moves:  10.a3  ,  10.Ned5  ,  10.Bd3  ,  10.g3  . }
10. g3 h5
{ Let's go! Played by Carlsen and a speciality of Moiseenko @@StartBracket@@a renowned expert on the Kalashnikov@@EndBracket@@. This already puts White in something of a dilemma: should he block this advance with h3, h4, or just ignore it?   For the record, the more orthodox  10...O-O  has been seen more often and is perfectly playable. }
11. a4
{ This is a rare move: my database indicates that only two games have taken this path. However, one of the games was played by England no.1 Michael Adams, so we should pay attention. However, Black can look forward to all the usual play and there is plenty of opportunities to stir up trouble. Troublemakers, follow me! }
11... b4 { keeping the queenside closed and pushing the knight. } 12. Ncd5 h4
{ Let's be consistent and keep pushing. Already White has a dilemma in how to deal with this.   Instead,  12...Nxe4?!  13.Bg2  f5  14.O-O  is a bit too risky for Black. The centre is opening and usually one would want to get castled quickly - but the h-pawn is hanging to the queen on d1. }
13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bc4
{ We are following the game Adams-Pert, England 2021. The English no.1 makes a pragmatic choice: instead of moving to g2 and getting hassled, he switches plans and lands on the traditional c4 square. }
14... hxg3
{ Black takes the initiative.   In the game I mentioned above, Nick Pert played  14...Be6  , and after lots of ups and downs, Adams won the game. Exchanging on g3 is stronger. }
15. fxg3 Bh3
{ Preventing White castling. To follow, Black may throw the knight in to d4, play ...Bg5. For White, the options are not so straightforward. }
