[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10. Kalashnikov 6.N1c3 - 8.Nc4 Mainline with 10.g3 h5"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 6.N1c3 - 8.Nc4 Main Line with 10.g3 h5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3
{ That already looks pleasant from Black's viewpoint. The knight has been sent back to a poor square. Much of the subsequent opening and middlegame struggle will centre on whether that knight can transfer to a decent square. }
7... Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nc4 b5
{ Forcing the knight to move again. This is overwhelmingly the most popular move.   Instead  8...Nf6  runs into  9.Bg5  with the threat to take on  f6  . }
9. Ne3
{ From White's viewpoint, the position has improved because the errant knight on a3 has succeeded in finding a better home on e3. But Black can also be content: the knight manoeuvres have cost White much time. }
9... Nf6
{ This is the starting point of the mainline of the 7...Be7 variation. From here there are four main moves:  10.a3  ,  10.Ned5  ,  10.Bd3  ,  10.g3  . }
10. g3 h5
{ Let's go! Played by Carlsen and a speciality of Moiseenko @@StartBracket@@a renowned expert on the Kalashnikov@@EndBracket@@. This already puts White in something of a dilemma: should he block this advance with h3, h4, or just ignore it?   For the record, the more orthodox  10...O-O  has been seen more often and is perfectly playable. }
11. Bg2 { This is by far the most popular response by White. } 11... h4 12. O-O
{ There is a difference in opinion among Kalashnikov players at this moment. The most popular moves are  12...h3  and  12...Nd4  , but I think it is best to keep options open with  12...Rb8  . By the way, it's best to avoid  12...hxg3  13.fxg3!  opening the f-file, which gives White play on the kingside. }
12... Rb8
{ A mysterious move! The rook often belongs here in the Kalashnikov. When the knight lands on d5 there is always a danger of a knight fork on b6 or c7, and this takes away some of that jeopardy.  The rook also supports the b-pawn making it easier to advance, or perhaps even capture if White advances the a-pawn. It is also a waiting move: White can't do much else here than plant the knight on d5, and we want to be able to exchange that off.   That's why the 'natural'  12...Be6  isn't appropriate here: after  13.Ncd5  we would lose a piece after  13...Nxd5  14.exd5  .  Notice that in these lines Black holds back with the h-pawn: later on, it might advance to h3, but exchanging is also an option.  Let's see how White reacts first. That's also the reason that Black is delaying castling: the rook could still prove useful on h8. With the centre relatively closed, the king can live in the middle for the moment. }
13. Ncd5
{ It is difficult to think of another move for White. The knight lands on the destined square. }
13... Nxd5
{ Let's exchange and find out which way White is going to recapture. He might get it wrong! }
14. exd5
{ In principle, from Black's viewpoint, that's the recapture we welcome: I would much rather see a dead pawn on d5 than a knight looming over the ramparts @@StartBracket@@although we have ways of dealing with that@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Nd4
{ The knight leaps to a beautiful outpost. Is it in danger of getting trapped here? }
15. g4
{ A wild attempt to trap the knight by taking away the f5 square, but White's kingside is severely weakened }
15... h3
{ After this the g4 pawn looks even more exposed, and who knows when that h3 pawn could help in a mating net. Hehe. }
16. Be4 { White threatens to trap the knight with pawn to c3. } 16... b4
{ Making room for the knight on b5. } 17. c3 Nb5
{ Better than exchanging on c3 as White is unable to push the knight away with a4. We have seen this idea before in a similar line. }
18. cxb4 Bg5
{ Highlighting the drawbacks of advancing with g4: the f4 square is weak. By the way, there is no need for Black to castle at the moment: the rook is doing a good job supporting the h-pawn and the king is safe enough as the centre is closed. }
19. Kh1 Nd4
{ Black has excellent compensation for the pawn in the form of strong pieces and White's ragged kingside. }
*

