{ Let's exchange and find out which way White is going to recapture. He might get it wrong! }
14. exd5
{ In principle, from Black's viewpoint, that's the recapture we welcome: I would much rather see a dead pawn on d5 than a knight looming over the ramparts @@StartBracket@@although we have ways of dealing with that@@EndBracket@@. }
14... Nd4
{ The knight leaps to a beautiful outpost. Is it in danger of getting trapped here? }
15. Qd3
{ The queen covers the f5 square, so c3, trapping the knight, is threatened. }
15... g6 16. c3
{ We are following the game Willow-Pert, British Championship 2019. I feature this in the 'Model Games' chapter. }
16... Nf5 { A safe and strong position for the knight. } 17. a4
{ At this moment in the game Pert exchanged on g3, and won a fine game, but there was something even stronger. }
17... bxa4 18. Rxa4 Nxe3 19. Qxe3
{ Recapturing with the queen looks awkward, but the bishop has to protect the b2 pawn. }
19... Bd7 20. Ra3 Qc8
{ Taking control of the c8-h3 diagonal and perhaps preparing ...Bh3. The h-file beckons for the queen! There is also another devilish point to the queen move. And, more prosaically, the a-pawn is defended. }
21. b3 Bd8
{ I love this manoeuvre! We see it so often in the Kalashnikov, but this is very special. The bishop hits b6 and can play a direct role in the attack on White's king. It also enables Black to play pawn to a5, securing the queenside and fixing the b3 pawn as a target. Don't forget that ...Bh3 is also a possibility.   Black has a strong initiative. }
