{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nc4 b5
{ Forcing the knight to move again. This is overwhelmingly the most popular move.   Instead  8...Nf6  runs into  9.Bg5  with the threat to take on  f6  . }
9. Ne3 Nf6 10. g3 O-O
{ If the aggression of  10...h5  isn't to your taste, then there is a more solid option that has fared decently for Black.   In databases you will find this has been a more popular move than  10...h5  . Which one you choose is perhaps just a question of taste. }
11. Bg2 b4
{ This is by far the most popular move at this point. Black aims to exchange pieces which will free his game.   One could develop in a different way:  11...Be6  12.O-O  Rc8  13.Ncd5  Na5  has given Black reasonable results. }
12. Ncd5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bg5
{ White has established the knight on d5, but it has taken some time to get there, and that gives Black the time to exchange off the 'bad bishop'. }
14. Bxg5 Qxg5
{ In principle the exchange is desirable for Black, but just for a moment the queen is offside - clearly, there is no way to attack White's solid kingside position. }
15. O-O Rb8
{ Covering the advanced b-pawn pre-empts White's attack with a3, and rules out an attack with Nc7. }
16. a3
{ This doesn't make much sense when Black's rook is positioned on b8, but let's take a look anyway. }
16... bxa3
{ White cannot recapture with the rook as the b2 pawn is en prise. Recapturing with the b-pawn splits the queenside pawns. Therefore White's next move is necessary, it all feels rather time-consuming. }
17. b3
{ This secures the b-pawn. White would like to recapture with the rook on a3 and then apply pressure to the lone a-pawn, but in the meantime, Black can generate counterplay. }
17... Bg4
{ A disruptive move, inducing a less-than-desirable block or pushing the queen to a tactically sensitive square. }
18. Bf3 Bh3
{ Black does best to keep up the pressure, although  18...Bxf3  19.Qxf3  Rfc8  is also playable. }
19. Re1
{ This allows Black to take the initiative. The more prudent choice is  19.Bg2  Bg4  which repeats the position. }
19... f5
{ Black takes the initiative on the kingside. Advancing the pawn again followed, potentially, by ...Rb8-b7-f7 is uncomfortable for White. }
