[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Kalashnikov 6.c4 Mainline with 9.Nc2"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 6.c4 Main Line with 9.Nc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4
{ White clamps the middle of the board and makes absolutely sure of squashing the pawn break ...d5. Think again! As we shall see, Black has devilishly dynamic chances and in the mainline, that is precisely the pawn move we will be looking to unleash.   That said, we should not underestimate this version of the Maroczy Bind: it is important we understand how to create counterplay or Black will get squashed.   Aside from  6.N1c3  , this is the other main line of the Kalashnikov Variation. }
6... Be6
{ As usual, this is an excellent square for the bishop, covering the d5 square and also looking at the c4 pawn.   The older way of playing this position was  6...Be7  7.N1c3  a6  8.Na3  Be6  9.Nc2  Bg5  10.Be2  Bxc1  11.Rxc1  . While it is positionally sound to exchange off these bishops I feel it loses too much time, allowing White to develop rapidly and establish strong control in the centre.   For reference, I invite you to look up the game Carlsen-Hou, Tata Steel 2015 where Black was reduced to passivity. }
7. N1c3
{ The vast majority bring out the knight here, conforming to standard opening principles. However, move-order can be fairly fluid in this line: bishops are developed at different times to e2 or e3 and sometimes elsewhere.   7.Be2  and  7.Bd3  are examined in separate chapters. }
7... a6
{ The knight is pushed away to a poor square. It is going to take a long time for White to recycle the poor beast to a better location, and in the meantime, Black can stir up trouble. }
8. Na3 g6
{ In the early days of the Kalashnikov, most players developed their bishop to e7, but the fianchetto is far more dynamic. This has been championed by the Iranian prodigy Parham Maghsoodloo. }
9. Nc2
{ Move order is flexible. Most players like to play the knight to c2 to cover the d4 square - and I think that is the most sensible.   Others prefer to develop with  9.Be3  or  9.Be2  . Very often these lines transpose. I will point out where these variations have independent significance. From Black's viewpoint matters are much clearer: in most cases, the next moves will be ...Bg7, ...Nf6, ...O-O - and then let's think again! }
9... Bg7 10. Be3 Nf6
{ This is the best square for the knight, putting pressure on the e4 pawn, looking at the g4 square, perhaps moving to h5, and covering the d5 square. In the old days of this variation, Black automatically put the knight on e7, but it is far less effective there as it cannot find another good square to move to. }
11. Be2 { The bishop prevents the knight from moving to g4 and h5. } 11... O-O
12. O-O
{ Both sides have developed sensibly and brought their kings to safety. Let the middlegame battle begin! }
12... Rc8
{ This is where the rook belongs. The c-file is going to be a great source of counterplay for Black.  In the past, such positions were thought to be better for White because of the supposedly weak pawn on d6. Let's reframe our thinking. This is a kind of Hedgehog position where with a couple of pawn breaks Black's pieces will be unleashed. }
13. Qd2
{ It is essential that Black plays actively before White has a chance to take a grip over the centre. There are two ways for Black to do this. }
13... Ne7
{ The c4 pawn is attacked. White has a few ways to deal with the threat. } 14.
Rfd1 { White plays for activity and generously gives Black a pawn. } 14... Bxc4
{ Thank you. It would be impolite to decline the offer. } 15. Bxc4 Rxc4
{ Not only is Black a pawn up, but there is also pressure on the c-file and the e4 pawn. }
16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. Rxd6 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Rxe4
{ More or less a forced sequence. White can recover the pawn. } 19. Rd7 Nf5 20.
Rxb7 a5
{ Black has active pieces, the rook on f8 is ready to join the battle, and White has a weak back rank. The pawn structure is favourable too: the kingside pawn majority provides central control and the minority attack on the queenside should not be underestimated. In the game Reprun-Y.Naiditsch, Jerusalem 2021, Black succeeded in winning. }
*

