{ Both sides have developed sensibly and brought their kings to safety. Let the middlegame battle begin! }
12... Rc8
{ This is where the rook belongs. The c-file is going to be a great source of counterplay for Black.  In the past, such positions were thought to be better for White because of the supposedly weak pawn on d6. Let's reframe our thinking. This is a kind of Hedgehog position where with a couple of pawn breaks Black's pieces will be unleashed. }
13. Qd2
{ It is essential that Black plays actively before White has a chance to take a grip over the centre. There are two ways for Black to do this. }
13... Ne7
{ The c4 pawn is attacked. White has a few ways to deal with the threat. } 14.
Na3
{ The knight returns to the side of the board: it's not the best location but it does hold the centre together. }
14... Nc6 { The knight returns, looking at the d4 square. } 15. Rfd1 Nd4
{ That is the move! Under no circumstances should Black meekly defend the d-pawn. Activity is everything! }
16. Rac1 Ng4
{ It's good to take one of the bishops, but not if we have to give up the pride of the position, the knight on d4. We want to move the king's knight anyway, to let the bishop on g7 into the game and potentially free the f-pawn. Let's start some action on the kingside.   By the way, the more standard  16...Nd7  is also a sound move. }
17. Bxg4 Bxg4 18. Re1 { Instead  18.f3?  Bxf3  wins material. Sneaky. } 18...
Qh4 { Increasing pressure on the kingside. It's easy for White to go wrong... }
19. Bxd4
{ Exchanging is White's best in this situation, although parting with the dark-squared bishop is not an easy decision to make. }
19... exd4 20. Nd5 Rfe8
{ With the two bishops, rooks on the semi-open files, and potential to attack on the kingside, Black can look forward with confidence. }
