[Round "?"]
[White "13. Kalashnikov 6.c4 Sidelines"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 6.c4 Be6 7.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4
{ White clamps the middle of the board and makes absolutely sure of squashing the pawn break ...d5. Think again! As we shall see, Black has devilishly dynamic chances and in the mainline, that is precisely the pawn move we will be looking to unleash.   That said, we should not underestimate this version of the Maroczy Bind: it is important we understand how to create counterplay or Black will get squashed.   Aside from  6.N1c3  , this is the other main line of the Kalashnikov Variation. }
6... Be6
{ As usual, this is an excellent square for the bishop, covering the d5 square and also looking at the c4 pawn.   The older way of playing this position was  6...Be7  7.N1c3  a6  8.Na3  Be6  9.Nc2  Bg5  10.Be2  Bxc1  11.Rxc1  . While it is positionally sound to exchange off these bishops I feel it loses too much time, allowing White to develop rapidly and establish strong control in the centre.   For reference, I invite you to look up the game Carlsen-Hou, Tata Steel 2015 where Black was reduced to passivity. }
7. Be2
{ Unpretentious development.  7.N1c3  is the most popular move and I am treating it as the mainline.   7.Bd3  is also possible and you will find that in another chapter. }
7... a6 8. N5c3
{ If the knight had gone back to a3 the game would in all likelihood transpose to one of the main lines, but retreating here takes the game in a different direction as the knight on b1 has the potential to move to d2 - a different circuit to the more usual a3-c2. }
8... Nf6
{ The knight belongs on this square, putting pressure on the e4 pawn.   Incidentally,  8...g6  is sometimes played here and should transpose to my mainline. }
9. Be3
{ Covering the d4 square, discouraging Black's knight from leaping forward. }
9... g6 10. Nd5
{ This move gives the line independent significance. Not that it is particularly good for White!   Instead of this,  10.O-O  Bg7  11.Na3  will transpose to the mainline. See also Anand-Maghsoodloo in the model games section. }
10... Bxd5
{ White was threatening to play Bb6 and Nc7+, so the knight must be eliminated. }
11. exd5
{ This is the move that we would like to see on the board as it creates an imbalance. Black has a healthy kingside pawn majority, White's isn't going very far. }
11... Ne7 { The knight will soon swing round to a better square. } 12. Nc3 Nf5
{ Please let me get that bishop! The dark squares would be there for the taking... }
13. Bg5 Bg7
{ We have been following the game Quparadze-Rapport where the Hungarian played  13...Be7  - which was reasonable - but I think it is better to fianchetto the bishop, as usual. }
14. O-O O-O
{ The bishop on g5 can be driven away by the h-pawn and the knight will land on d4. Black is very comfortable. }
*

