1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4
{ White clamps the middle of the board and makes absolutely sure of squashing the pawn break ...d5. Think again! As we shall see, Black has devilishly dynamic chances and in the mainline, that is precisely the pawn move we will be looking to unleash.   That said, we should not underestimate this version of the Maroczy Bind: it is important we understand how to create counterplay or Black will get squashed.   Aside from  6.N1c3  , this is the other main line of the Kalashnikov Variation. }
6... Be6
{ As usual, this is an excellent square for the bishop, covering the d5 square and also looking at the c4 pawn.   The older way of playing this position was  6...Be7  7.N1c3  a6  8.Na3  Be6  9.Nc2  Bg5  10.Be2  Bxc1  11.Rxc1  . While it is positionally sound to exchange off these bishops I feel it loses too much time, allowing White to develop rapidly and establish strong control in the centre.   For reference, I invite you to look up the game Carlsen-Hou, Tata Steel 2015 where Black was reduced to passivity. }
7. Be2
{ Unpretentious development.  7.N1c3  is the most popular move and I am treating it as the mainline.   7.Bd3  is also possible and you will find that in another chapter. }
7... a6 8. N5c3
{ If the knight had gone back to a3 the game would in all likelihood transpose to one of the main lines, but retreating here takes the game in a different direction as the knight on b1 has the potential to move to d2 - a different circuit to the more usual a3-c2. }
8... Nf6
{ The knight belongs on this square, putting pressure on the e4 pawn.   Incidentally,  8...g6  is sometimes played here and should transpose to my mainline. }
9. Be3
{ Covering the d4 square, discouraging Black's knight from leaping forward. }
9... g6 10. Nd5
{ This move gives the line independent significance. Not that it is particularly good for White!   Instead of this,  10.O-O  Bg7  11.Na3  will transpose to the mainline. See also Anand-Maghsoodloo in the model games section. }
10... Bxd5
{ White was threatening to play Bb6 and Nc7+, so the knight must be eliminated. }
11. cxd5 Nd4
{ This kind of pawn sacrifice should be second nature in the Kalashnikov: if White takes, the bishop on g7 turns into a monster and Black gets superb control over the dark squares.   Compare what happens if Black makes the normal retreat:  11...Ne7  12.Nd2  Bg7  13.Qa4+  b5  14.Qb3  O-O  15.a4  . White's initiative on the queenside is potent, the bishops look great, and Black has no counterplay. }
12. Bxd4
{ White doesn't have to exchange off the knight but taking the pawn is obviously the critical test from Black's viewpoint. }
12... exd4 13. Qxd4 Bg7
{ In taking the pawn White has had to give up his dark-squared bishop, and that turns the bishop on g7 into a fearsome, unopposed beast. }
14. Nc3 O-O 15. O-O Re8
{ The right place for the rook. Black threatens ...Nxe4, so White's queen has to move. }
16. Qd3 { Instead  16.Qb4  b5  offers Black good compensation for the pawn. }
16... Nd7
{ Up until this move, we were following the game Quparadze-Rapport, Riyadh 2017 where the Hungarian deviated with the move  16...Qb6  and won a nice game @@StartBracket@@see the 'Model Games' chapter@@EndBracket@@. But  16...Nd7  is even stronger. It is very hard for White to hold on to the extra pawn.   The immediate threat is ...Nc5 followed by taking on c3 and taking on e4.   17.f3  fails to  17...Qb6+  and 18...Qxb2 . White's big problem is the light-squared bishop: with the pawn on d5 its movement will always be restricted and the more nimble knight ensures that Black keeps a positional advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14. Kalashnikov 6.c4 Be6 7.Bd3"]
[Black "Kalashnikov 6.c4 Be6 7.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4
{ White clamps the middle of the board and makes absolutely sure of squashing the pawn break ...d5. Think again! As we shall see, Black has devilishly dynamic chances and in the mainline, that is precisely the pawn move we will be looking to unleash.   That said, we should not underestimate this version of the Maroczy Bind: it is important we understand how to create counterplay or Black will get squashed.   Aside from  6.N1c3  , this is the other main line of the Kalashnikov Variation. }
6... Be6
{ As usual, this is an excellent square for the bishop, covering the d5 square and also looking at the c4 pawn.   The older way of playing this position was  6...Be7  7.N1c3  a6  8.Na3  Be6  9.Nc2  Bg5  10.Be2  Bxc1  11.Rxc1  . While it is positionally sound to exchange off these bishops I feel it loses too much time, allowing White to develop rapidly and establish strong control in the centre.   For reference, I invite you to look up the game Carlsen-Hou, Tata Steel 2015 where Black was reduced to passivity. }
7. Bd3
{ Common enough, although I should mention that in the vast majority of games White plays the standard developing move  7.N1c3  . Move order is flexible, so variations often transpose, and therefore a good knowledge of general strategy is important - I recommend the 'Model Games' chapter!.  One advantage of playing the bishop to d3 is that it won't be in the range of Black's knight if it should land on d4. Another point is that the e4 pawn is protected making it easier for the knight to hop to d5. A disadvantage of the bishop move is that applying pressure to the d6 pawn is less easy. }
7... Nf6 { Black carries on developing normally. } 8. O-O
{ If White ever plays  8.N1c3  , then push back the knight:  8...a6!  9.Na3  . That's not a good square. We will deal with this possibility @@StartBracket@@by transposition@@EndBracket@@ in a couple of moves. }
8... g6
{ I like the fianchetto: on the long diagonal the bishop offers dynamic counter-chances. }
9. N1c3 { This blocks out the other knight on b5. } 9... a6
{ Good move. The knight is pushed to a poor square on a3. } 10. Na3 Bg7
{ Sound development. } 11. Nc2 { The knight redeploys to a better square. }
11... O-O 12. h3
{ Preparing to play Be3 - otherwise, the bishop will be hit by ...Ng4. } 12...
Rc8
{ The knight wasn't well placed on a3 - true. But moving away from there leaves the c4 pawn vulnerable. }
13. Be3 { White is unaware of the danger. } 13... Na5
{ White has to defend the c-pawn with the pawn. } 14. b3 b5
{ Exploiting the loose knight on c3. This is a typical tactic in this line: it's one of the reasons we played the rook to c8. }
*

