1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4
{ White clamps the middle of the board and makes absolutely sure of squashing the pawn break ...d5. Think again! As we shall see, Black has devilishly dynamic chances and in the mainline, that is precisely the pawn move we will be looking to unleash.   That said, we should not underestimate this version of the Maroczy Bind: it is important we understand how to create counterplay or Black will get squashed.   Aside from  6.N1c3  , this is the other main line of the Kalashnikov Variation. }
6... Be6
{ As usual, this is an excellent square for the bishop, covering the d5 square and also looking at the c4 pawn.   The older way of playing this position was  6...Be7  7.N1c3  a6  8.Na3  Be6  9.Nc2  Bg5  10.Be2  Bxc1  11.Rxc1  . While it is positionally sound to exchange off these bishops I feel it loses too much time, allowing White to develop rapidly and establish strong control in the centre.   For reference, I invite you to look up the game Carlsen-Hou, Tata Steel 2015 where Black was reduced to passivity. }
7. Bd3
{ Common enough, although I should mention that in the vast majority of games White plays the standard developing move  7.N1c3  . Move order is flexible, so variations often transpose, and therefore a good knowledge of general strategy is important - I recommend the 'Model Games' chapter!.  One advantage of playing the bishop to d3 is that it won't be in the range of Black's knight if it should land on d4. Another point is that the e4 pawn is protected making it easier for the knight to hop to d5. A disadvantage of the bishop move is that applying pressure to the d6 pawn is less easy. }
7... Nf6 { Black carries on developing normally. } 8. O-O
{ If White ever plays  8.N1c3  , then push back the knight:  8...a6!  9.Na3  . That's not a good square. We will deal with this possibility @@StartBracket@@by transposition@@EndBracket@@ in a couple of moves. }
8... g6
{ I like the fianchetto: on the long diagonal the bishop offers dynamic counter-chances. }
9. b3
{ Once White plays b3, Black has to watch out for the bishop emerging on a3, attacking the d6 pawn. Therefore at this moment, the knight has to be pushed back. }
9... a6
{ After the knight is pushed back, the pressure on the d6 pawn is removed. }
10. N5c3 Bg7
{ It is easy to see how the bishop can support the knight jumping into the d4 square. This highlights the disadvantage of the @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2np4/1N2p3/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c4  variation.  Yes, the c-pawn gives White a clamp on the d5 square, but it comes at a price: there is a big hole on d4. Besides, there are ways to chip away at White's center. }
11. Nd5 { The most straightforward move. } 11... Bxd5
{ Let's get rid of that knight immediately and see how White intends recapturing. }
12. cxd5 Nd4
{ The knight in the middle of the board is irritating for White: it cannot be left there, it must be exchanged off or Black will simply stand better. }
13. Nc3 O-O { Now we have time to bring the king to safety. } 14. Bb2 Nd7
{ This is a key move in the Kalashnikov, particularly in the variations with @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp3ppp/2np4/1N2p3/4P3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.c4  . The knight allows the bishop on g7 to have more influence on the game and can jump to c5. Sometimes, it might also be possible to throw the f-pawn up the board, although that can rebound on Black, so prepare carefully. }
15. Ne2 Nxe2+
{ The knight has done its job and it can go back in the box with a clear conscience. }
16. Qxe2 Nc5
{ I think it is best to secure the position of the knight before advancing on the kingside. }
17. Bc2 a5
{ Preventing White from pushing away the knight with b4. Black can combine play on both sides of the board: ....Rc8, ...Bh6, and if the circumstances are right, perhaps ...f5. }
