[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Postupalsky Mikhail vs. Burimov Sergey, Tula, 2005"]
[Result "*"]

{ These games contain the most important strategies and themes in the Kalashnikov. Get to know them, and when to apply them, and you will have gained a good understanding of the opening so that even if you can't recall the exact move I recommend in the course, you will be able to navigate your way through the middlegame. Let me mention a few of the themes you will be encountering in these games: the ...d5 pawn break; the e and f pawn attack; the queenside minority attack; the bad-bishop bounce; establishing a knight on d4; sacrificing a pawn with ...Nd4; the f5 pawn break; what happens when your opponent breaks with f4; the h-file attack; sacrificing the d6 pawn; breaking the Maroczy Bind with ...b5. }
1. e4
{ In this game we see the ...d5 pawn break. This is perhaps the most common and most important early middlegame strategy in the Kalashnikov. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nf5
{ As you can see in the course, this move is not at all challenging and gives Black the opportunity to break in the centre straightaway. }
5... d5
{ The pawn break immediately liberates Black's pieces. It usually isn't quite as easy to execute as here! }
6. Ng3 { A poor move, wasting time. } 6... Nf6
{ Black already has a lead in development. } 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. Qxd5 Nxd5
{ It is interesting to see that Black headed into the endgame: he is confident that he can still use his lead in development and superior pawn structure. After the pawn break, Black has an extra centre pawn @@StartBracket@@e5@@EndBracket@@ which provides him with greater control in the middle of the board. }
9. c3 Be6 10. Be2 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2
{ Evidently, Black's pieces are well centralised and harmoniously placed. There is nothing to thwart the natural plan of advancing the kingside pawn majority. }
12... f5
{ This is often an excellent plan when the queens are on the board as it can set up a kingside attack. Even in this endgame, the pawns are dangerous, preventing White's minor pieces from occupying decent squares. }
13. Kh1 Rad8 14. Nf3 h6 15. Bc4 e4 16. Re1
{ If  16.Nd2  Ne5  17.Bb3  Nd3  A picture of centralisation! } 16... Nc7 17.
Bxe6+ Nxe6 18. Nd2 Nc5 19. Nc4 Nd3
{ Many moves ago White played the pawn to c3 to prevent Black's knights from moving into the b4 and d4 squares, but it created a huge hole which has been occupied by a rangy octopus knight. What central control! This is a logical consequence of the pawn break at move five. }
20. Rf1 b5 21. Na3 Bxa3 22. bxa3 Nce5
{ Knight no.2 enters the fray with cover from the central pawns. } 23. Be3
{ A blunder but it's miserable anyway.   23.Kg1  Rc8  keeps up the pressure. }
23... f4 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Veress Robert vs. Horvath Peter, Hungary, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

{ The d5 pawn break. Another example, but this time it takes longer to achieve and White does not stand that badly. Nevertheless, Black's central control allows him to dominate. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3 Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Be3 { This has also been relatively popular. } 8... Nf6 9. Nc4 O-O
{ 9...b5  is my repertoire recommendation, but castling is also quite reasonable. }
10. Nb6 Rb8 11. Be2 Be6 12. O-O
{ At the moment White has a bind over the b6 and d5 squares and it is hard to imagine that Black will ever break out. Watch this space. }
12... Nd7
{ First, the knight on b6 is challenged and this also opens the diagonal for the bishop on e7. }
13. Nxd7
{ 13.Nbd5  would be met by  13...Bg5  and Black gains more freedom after the exchange of bishops. The knight on c6 will be able to occupy the d4 square. }
13... Qxd7 14. Nd5 Bd8
{ The bad-bishop bounce. A common manoeuvre. In this game, the bishop does not stay on the board for much longer, but we can often see that emerging on b6 is another great way for Black to gain more activity and freedom, or simply to exchange off dark-squared bishops, securing control over the d4 square @@StartBracket@@for example@@EndBracket@@. Look out for this in another of the model games. }
15. Nb6
{ 15.a4  Ne7  would continue to fight against White's control over the d5 square. }
15... Bxb6 16. Bxb6
{ Black has a choice. To break with ...d5 or ...f5? Or something else? } 16...
Ne7
{ This threatens ...Qc6.   16...f5  In this case I would prefer not to move my f-pawn for fear of the long-term weakness of my king, but it is playable:  17.exf5  Bxf5  18.c4  Rbe8  with decent piece activity.   16...d5?  Strategic guidelines can be helpful, but each position should be judged on its own merits, and in this case the pawn break is premature:  17.exd5  Qxd5  18.Qxd5  Bxd5  19.Rfd1  The bishop on b6 prevents Black's rooks from occupying the open file and, combined with the two bishops, White has a serious endgame advantage. }
17. f3 Qc6 18. Bf2 d5
{ Now that the bishop has been driven away, the break is fine. } 19. exd5 Nxd5
{ What a transformation over the last few moves. White's bind over b6 and d5 has been shaken off and Black controls the centre. The threat is to put a rook on the d-file opposite White's queen. }
20. Bd3 Nf4 21. Re1
{ 21.Be4  Qc7  22.Qd2  f5  23.Bd3  Rbd8  maintains the pressure. } 21... f6
{ Black's extra centre pawn and solid pawn chain give him good control over the centre. This is so often the case after Black breaks with ...d5. }
22. Bf1 Rbd8 23. Qc1 Bf5 24. c4
{ White is under pressure, but this is a dreadful move, weakening the d3 square. Compare this with Postupalsky-Burimov where Black also succeeded in occupying the d3 square. }
24... Bd3 25. Qc3 Bxf1 26. Kxf1 Rd3
{ 26...Nd3  27.Re3  Nxf2  28.Kxf2  Rd4  29.Rc1  Rfd8  is another way to play, with domination of the d-file. }
27. Qc2 Rfd8 28. Be3 Ne6 29. b3 Qd7 30. Ke2
{ An awful misjudgment. The king gets cut to shreds in the middle.   30.Kg1  would have kept White in the game, although Black's superiority is clear. }
30... Nd4+ 31. Bxd4 Qxd4 32. Rad1 e4
{ The position opens and that spells the end for the king.  In this game the d5 break gave Black excellent central control. This time, the advance of the e and f pawn duo wasn't possible, but the occupation of the weakened d3 square was once again a theme. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Szalanczy Emil vs. Dokhoian Yury,Cattaolica, 1993"]
[Result "*"]

{ Don't be put off by the move order of this game. The variation can also arise from a Kalashnikov  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  5.Nb5  d6  6.Be3  , but more than that, the themes that arise are common to many Kalashnikov games. This is a great lesson in middlegame play by Garry Kasparov's former coach. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 e5 7. Ndb5 a6 8.
Na3 b5 9. Nd5
{ Black would like to play  9...Nxe4  , but then  10.Bb6  and Nc7+. } 9... Rb8
10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. c4 b4 12. Nb1 a5 13. Nd2 Qg6 14. h4 Be7 15. g3 O-O 16. Bg2
{ It appears as though White has a firm grip over the centre, but there are weaknesses that Black can exploit. }
16... Bd8
{ An excellent example of the bad-bishop bounce. Very often this bishop emerges on g5 - which is impossible here. However, there is another route to freedom via d8. }
17. O-O Bb6 18. Bxb6 Rxb6
{ The exchange of bishops will help Black to establish the knight on the monster d4 square. }
19. Rc1 Rd8
{ 19...Nd4  would be inaccurate:  20.Nb3  exchanges off the knight on d4 @@StartBracket@@or it has to retreat@@EndBracket@@ and Black's position loses its dynamism. }
20. Re1 Bg4 21. Bf3 Bd7 22. Re3 Nd4 { The right moment. } 23. Bh5
{ 23.Nb3  would be met by  23...Ba4  . After Black exchanges off the bishop for the knight, the knight on d4 can't be displaced and strategically Black is in command. }
23... Qh6 24. Bg4 Bxg4 25. Qxg4 Qe6 26. Qh5
{ White would have done better to exchange queens as Black manages to develop a fierce attack. }
26... Rc6
{ The rook attacks the pawn on c4 and prevents the knight on b3 from moving. }
27. Kg2 Rf8
{ Time for the breakthrough. Clearly, the d-pawn isn't going anywhere, but cracking open the f-file is great, particularly in combination with the knight on d4. }
28. b3 f5 29. Nf3 { 29.exf5  Rxf5  30.Qd1  Rc8  is very dangerous. } 29... fxe4
30. Nd2 { 30.Ng5  Qf5  wins. } 30... Rf5 31. Qd1 Rc8 32. Nxe4 Rcf8 33. Qd3 Qg6
34. Rd1 Qg4
{ I can imagine that time pressure was involved as Dokhoian prevaricates - but he does not spoil his position.   34...R5f7  Threatens ...Nf5 and forces the king to a poor square.  35.Kh3  Rf3  and all the pressure is on White. }
35. Rd2 Qg6 36. Ng5 h6 37. Ne4 Kh8 38. c5 dxc5 39. Nxc5 Qc6+ 40. Ne4 Nf3 41.
Qd5 Qg6
{ White finally cracks under the sustained pressure and loses material: both the rook and the pawn on h4 are hanging. }
42. Rxf3 Rxf3 43. Qxe5 R3f5 44. Qd4 Rf4 45. Re2 Re8 46. h5 Qxh5 47. gxf4 Qxe2
48. Ng3 Qb5 49. Qd6 Qb8 50. Qd7 Qa8+ 51. f3 Qd8 52. Qg4 Qd2+ 53. Kh3 Qxa2 54.
Nh5 Qa1 55. Qd7 Rg8 56. f5 a4 57. Nf4 axb3 58. Ng6+ Kh7 59. Qd3 Qf6 60. f4 b2
61. Kg4 Rd8 62. Qe4 Qd4 63. Qb1 Qd1+
{ There are three main lessons from this game: the bad-bishop bounce from e7-d8-b6 exchanged off the dark-squared bishops; that in turn enabled the knight to land on the d4 square; the ...f5 pawn break opened the f-file and created pressure on White's kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Furlan Miha vs. Romanishin Oleg M, Croatia, 1999"]
[Result "*"]

{ Black plays the Taimanov Sicilian, but the game quickly reaches a position that can arise from the Kalashnikov by transposition. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nb5 d6 6. Bf4 e5 7. Be3 a6 8. N5c3
Nf6 9. Bg5 Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. Bc4 O-O 12. O-O Be6 13. Nd5
{ This position can arise from two variations of the Kalashnikov: @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/2n1p3/8/3NP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Nb5  d6  6.N5c3  , as well as 6. Bc4, and this position-type, where White exchanges on f6 and plays the knight into d5 is generic.  (In other words, it's worth getting to know the strategic options for Black.) }
13... Bg5
{ A good start: the bishop finds an unopposed diagonal. This has to be the most common manoeuvre in the Kalashnikov @@StartBracket@@although watch out for its close relation, the bad-bishop bounce ...Bd8-b6, which is a bit harder to achieve@@EndBracket@@. }
14. Bb3 Rc8
{ As in most Sicilians, there could well be some action on the c-file, and this is where the rook belongs. }
15. Re1
{ If White had played  15.c3  Black would chase the bishop anyway.  15...Na5   And  15.Nbc3  would be answered by  15...Nd4  - which is very annoying to cope with. }
15... Nd4 16. c3 Nxb3 17. axb3
{ By exchanging off the bishop, Black has succeeded in loosening White's hold over d5 and e4. }
17... f5
{ Advancing the f-pawn isn't always appropriate: while the intention is to open lines for Black's pieces, sometimes it can rebound, and Black's king comes under pressure. In this case, the light-squared bishop has been exchanged, so Black is safe on the b1-h7 diagonal. }
18. c4
{ With hindsight, White should have exchanged:  18.exf5  Bxf5  19.Nd2   19.c4  Qe8  20.Nbc3  Qg6  gives Black superb control over the diagonals.  19...Bxd2  Necessary, before the knight blockades on e4.   In this case,  19...Qe8  is too slow:  20.Ne4  and White has established control.  20.Qxd2  Be6  21.c4  Rf7  The bishop keeps guard over the knight, and chances are about equal. }
18... f4
{ Romanishin changes the nature of the position: this looks more like a King's Indian pawn storm. Here the push is appropriate, for two reasons: White has no significant counterplay in the middle of the board; and, once the light-squared bishop has been exchanged, Black has a good chance of pushing the g-pawn through the g4 square. }
19. f3 Bh4 20. Re2 g5 21. Nbc3
{ Instead,  21.Nd2  Rf7  followed by ...Rg7 and ...h5, and ...g4. } 21... g4
22. Kh1 Kh8 23. Rd2 Qg5
{ The attack is raging. Black threatens, among other things, ...Bg3 and ...Qh4. This is like a dream King's Indian Defence. }
24. Ne2 gxf3 25. gxf3 Rg8 26. Ng1 Rg6 27. Qf1 Rcg8
{ Black's strategy has needed no sophistication: triple on the g-file and see what turns up. White is hanging on by a thread. }
28. Nc3 Qd8 29. Nge2 Qb6
{ The queen bounce! As well as keeping an eye on events on the a7-g1 diagonal, the queen is simply able to snaffle the pawn on b3. Sooner or later, White is going to fall for a tactic. }
30. Rad1 Qxb3 31. Rxd6 Qxc4 32. Nd5 Bh3 33. Qxh3 Qxe2
{ White resigned. If  34.Nc3  Rxd6  and mate is not far off. This kind of direct pawn storm with ...f4 and ...g5-g4 is sometimes available to Black: but make sure the g-pawn can be pushed through. If White still has a light-squared bishop, there may well be better strategies. }
