[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Molano Lafuente, Ismael vs. Ikonnikov Vyacheslav, Barcelona , 2009"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3 Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nc4 b5
{ Forcing the knight to move again. This is overwhelmingly the most popular move.   Instead  8...Nf6  runs into  9.Bg5  with the threat to take on  f6  . }
9. Ne3 Nf6 10. Ned5 O-O 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. Nd5 Be6 13. c3 Bg5
{ The bad bishop finds an open diagonal. This is perhaps one of the most common and useful manoeuvres in the Kalashnikov. }
14. Be2 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Ne7
{ Black fights for control over the d5 square. White does best to exchange on e7 as Black threatens to exchange on d5 gaining a favourable pawn structure. }
16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. O-O
{ Having eliminated the knight on d5 Black has already achieved a comfortable position. The question is, what now? Two pawn breaks are possible - with the f pawn or the d pawn. In this case, I don't believe that  17...f5  is that effective as White has no weaknesses on the kingside:  18.exf5  Rxf5  is playable but after  19.a4  White has a little initiative. }
17... Rfd8 { Black goes for the ...d5 break. } 18. c4
{ 18.Bf3  prevents ...d5 but allows  18...Bxa2  19.b3  Qe6  and Black keeps the extra pawn. }
18... Qb7
{ An excellent square for the queen, pointing at two key points, b2 and e4.   Instead,  18...bxc4  19.Bxc4  would be equal: it is difficult to generate winning chances with the exchange of bishops. }
19. Qc2
{ 19.b3  bxc4  20.bxc4  holds on to all the material as the e-pawn is immune, but Black has managed to isolate the c4 pawn so has a structural advantage.  20...Rac8 }
19... Rac8 20. b3 Rc5 { Black's b-pawn puts serious pressure on the c4 pawn. }
21. Qd2
{ Blundering a pawn.   21.Rfd1  was better, but Black can pile up on the c-file.  21...Qc7  with uncomfortable pressure. }
21... bxc4 22. Bxc4 Bxc4 23. Rxc4 Rxc4 24. bxc4 Qxe4
{ Black has won a pawn and converted it into a win without drama. } 25. c5 Qc6
26. Qa5 Rc8 27. cxd6 Qxd6 28. Re1 g6 29. g3 Rc5 30. Qa4 Kg7 31. Rd1 Qe6 32. Re1
Rc4 33. Qb3 Qd5 34. Rd1 Qc5 35. Rd2 h5 36. Re2 Rc1+ 37. Kg2 Qc6+ 38. Kh3 Rg1
39. f3 Qd7+ 40. Kh4 f6 41. Re4 Qd2
{ The key moments from this game: Black played the bishop out to g5 relieving pressure; next White's control over the d5 square was contested with ...Ne7; Black built up pressure on the c4 pawn - a kind of minority attack. }
