[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Tomczak Jacek vs. Shirov Alexei, Trzcianka, 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N5c3
{ White does not want to move the knight back to a3 so drops back to c3 looking to occupy the d5 square. My repertoire recommendation here is to play the straightforward  6...Nf6  , but Shirov's move is also fine. }
6... Be7 7. Nd5 Nf6 8. Nxf6+ Bxf6 9. Nc3 O-O 10. g3 Bg5
{ The 'bad' bishop finds an open diagonal and breathes again. } 11. Bg2 Bxc1
12. Rxc1 Qb6
{ Shirov exploits the fact that White is a little behind in development to induce a weakness.  Black could have played the standard   12...Be6  with a satisfactory and decent position. }
13. b3
{ understandably, White did not want to play  13.Rb1  consigns the rook to a pawn's miserable defence, but the game continuation gives Black something to play on. }
13... Qa5 14. Qd2 Be6 15. a4
{ The normal move   15.O-O  runs into trouble:  15...Nd4  threatening ...Qxc3 and a nasty fork - a common tactic with the knight on d4. If  16.Kh1  Rac8  Exploits the wobbly position of the knight now that the pawn is no longer on b2.  17.Nb1  Qxa2  ...and White is about to drop a second pawn. }
15... Rfc8 16. Nb5 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2
{ White must have imagined that the endgame would bring solace, but Shirov quickly builds pressure on the weakened pawn structure. }
17... a6 18. Nc3 Nd4
{ If White does nothing, Black will double rooks on the c-file. } 19. Ne2 Nxe2
20. Kxe2 b5
{ Black uses the minority attack to create weaknesses.   20...Rc3  21.Kd2  Rac8  looks good, but it is hard for Black to make further progress. }
21. axb5
{ If  21.Rhd1  Kf8  22.Rxd6  Bxb3  23.axb5  axb5  24.Kd1  Bc4  Black has the better bishop and the rooks are well coordinated. }
21... axb5
{ Notice how Black's one queenside pawn on b5 holds back the b and c-pawns. In other words, it is a classic minority attack. }
22. Rhd1 Ra2 23. Rd2 { If  23.Rxd6  Bxb3  gives Black the advantage. } 23...
Kf8
{ The king runs into the middle to protect the e7 pawn - so often its best position in the endgame, and sometimes even in the middlegame. }
24. Bf1 Ke7 25. c4
{ White makes a lunge hoping to break free but it loses a pawn. However there weren't any promising options. For example:   25.Kd1  Bxb3  26.Bxb5   26.cxb3  Rxc1+  27.Kxc1  Ra1+  28.Kb2  Rxf1  with an extra pawn  26...Bc4  27.Bxc4  Rxc4  28.f3  Rc3  29.Rf2  Raa3  and the pressure continues. }
25... Ra3 26. Kd1 Rxb3 27. cxb5 Bg4+ 28. Be2 Bxe2+ 29. Rxe2 Rxc1+ 30. Kxc1 Rxb5
{ Black is a pawn up. Such endgames aren't always easy to win, but Shirov succeeds in creating more targets. }
31. Kd1 g5
{ Now the h-pawn is vulnerable @@StartBracket@@as well as the e4 pawn@@EndBracket@@ }
32. Ra2 Rb1+ 33. Ke2 Rh1 34. Kf3 Rxh2 35. Kg4 Kf6 36. Ra6 h5+ 37. Kf3 Ke6 38.
Ra8 g4+ 39. Ke2 h4 40. gxh4 g3 41. Re8+ Kd7 42. Rg8 gxf2 43. Rh8 d5 44. exd5 e4
45. Rh7 Ke8 46. d6 e3 47. d7+ Kd8 48. Rxf7 Rh1
{ This endgame illustrates an important facet of Black's position in the Kalashnikov: the pawn mass d6, e5, f7, g7, h7 is very healthy. While the a and b-pawns soften White's queenside pawns with a minority attack, the kingside pawn mass remains firm.   Key moments in this game: the bishop emerging on ...g5 @@StartBracket@@again!@@EndBracket@@; Black playing for a minority attack on the queenside. }
