[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Kiroski Toni vs. Eljanov Pavel, Ohrid, 2001"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3 Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Be3 Nf6 9. Nc4 O-O
{ My repertoire recommendation is  9...b5  10.Nb6  Rb8  11.Nxc8  Qxc8  which starts the immediate undermining of the pawn on e4. }
10. Bb6 Qd7 11. Be2 Rb8 12. Qd2 Bd8
{ White has a grip over the b6 and d5 squares which Black wants to loosen by exchanging pieces. }
13. Rd1 Bxb6 14. Nxb6 Qd8 15. Nxc8
{ White gets greedy and takes the d-pawn. A very risky decision considering that the king is still in the middle.   15.Nbd5  Be6  16.Nxf6+  Qxf6  17.O-O  Rbc8  was a quieter way for White to play, but Black is well coordinated. }
15... Rxc8 16. Qxd6 Qb6
{ If the b-pawn drops, White's queenside collapses, but defending the pawn is problematic. }
17. Qa3
{ 17.b3  would be disastrous:  17...Rfd8  18.Qa3  Nd4  19.Qb2  Rxc3  20.Qxc3  Nxe4  21.Qb2  Nxc2+  22.Qxc2  Qxf2  checkmate - for example! }
17... Nd4 { As ever, the centralised knight causes havoc. } 18. Bd3 Ng4
{ A bold thrust. One of the threats is ...Nxc2+ and ...Qf2 mate. } 19. O-O Qh6
{ Swinging the queen over feels very natural, but in fact there was a stronger move which would have won the game.   19...Nxh2!  Crushing.  20.Kxh2   20.Nd5  Nhf3+  21.gxf3  Qg6+  22.Kh2  Qh5+  23.Kg3  Qg5+  24.Kh3  Rfe8  preventing Ne7+ with a winning attack.   20.g3  Qh6  threatening ...Nf3+ and ...Qh2 mate.  21.Kg2  Ng4  22.Rh1  Qf6  23.Rd2  Ne3+  24.fxe3  Qf3+  25.Kg1  Qxg3+  26.Kf1  Qf3+  27.Kg1  Rc6  and a check on g6  28.Rhh2  Qxe3+  29.Rdf2  Rg6+  30.Kh1  Nf3  Notice how in these lines White's queen is stranded in Siberia, unable to take part in the defence. That is so often a consequence of capturing the pawn on d6.  20...Qh6+  21.Kg1   21.Kg3  Qf4+  22.Kh3  Rc6  and ...Rh6.  21...Nf3+  22.gxf3  Qg5+  23.Kh2  Rc6  and ...Rh6 }
20. h3 Nf3+ 21. Kh1
{ 21.gxf3  Qxh3  22.fxg4  Qxg4+  23.Kh2  Rc6  is similar to variations above. }
21... Ng5 22. f3 Nxh3 23. fxg4 Nf2+ 24. Kg1 Nxg4 25. Rf5
{ 25.Rf2  Qh2+  26.Kf1  Qh4  27.Rdd2  gives better chances of a defence according to my machine. }
25... Qh2+ 26. Kf1 Qh1+ 27. Ke2 Qxg2+ 28. Ke1 Qg3+ 29. Ke2 g6 30. Rdf1
{ 30.Rff1  Qe3  is White's problem } 30... gxf5 31. Nd5 fxe4 32. Ne7+ Kh8 33.
Bxe4 Qxa3 34. bxa3 Rc7 35. Nd5 Rc4 36. Bf5 Rd8
{ There are many positions in the opening where White is able to capture the pawn on d6. It is rarely a good idea. In most cases, Black is able to generate a quick attack. It is worth remembering that in many lines White makes multiple knight moves in the Kalashnikov, and is already behind in development. Therefore capturing a pawn, liberating Black's pieces, is often a perilous exercise. }
