[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Corrales Jimenez Fidel vs. Alvarez Marquez Johan, Havana, 2008"]
[Result "*"]

{ Here is another game where White foolishly captures the pawn on d6 in the opening. The consequences are catastrophic. }
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3 Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nd5 Nf6 9. Nxf6+ Bxf6 10. Nc4 O-O 11. Nxd6
{ A reckless decision considering that the knight is White's only piece in play and he has yet to castle.  11.c3  is more prudent. }
11... Be6
{ Black doesn't need to go crazy: it is enough to bring some pieces into play. }
12. c3 Qc7 { Threatening a pin with a rook. } 13. Nf5 Rfd8
{ In the repertoire I recommend  13...Rad8  but the game continuation is also dangerous. }
14. Qf3 Qa5
{ Excellent move. Black uses the pin to play the knight into the middle. White's lack of development is shocking. }
15. Be2 Bxf5 16. exf5
{ 16.Qxf5  Nd4  hits the queen and threatens a winning check. } 16... e4
{ The bishop is unleashed. } 17. Qh5
{ 17.Qxe4  Re8   17...Bxc3+  18.Kf1  Re8  19.Qc2  Bf6  20.Be3  Rac8  also gives Black a wonderful initiative.  18.Qb1  Nd4  19.Be3  Nxe2  20.Kxe2  Qb5+  leaves the king stranded in the middle of the board and the attack rages on. }
17... Bxc3+ 18. Kf1 Bd2 19. g3 g6 20. fxg6 Qxh5 21. Bxh5 hxg6 22. Bd1 Bxc1 23.
Rxc1 Rd2
{ Material is even, but the rook on the seventh cuts through White's position and the attack persists. }
24. Bc2 e3 25. fxe3 Ne5 26. Be4 Rad8 27. h3 Rxb2 28. Rg1 Nc4
{ The knight cannot be taken because of ...Rd1 mate. White's king never escaped from the middle which meant he could never bring the king's rook into play, justice after the injudicious pawn grab. For the most part, Black did not play any extraordinary moves in order to exploit his lead in development, although I would mention one move that was clever:@@StartFEN@@r2r2k1/1pq2ppp/p1n1bb2/4pN2/4P3/2P2Q2/PP3PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQ - 4 14@@EndFEN@@  14...Qa5  preparing ...Nd4. }
