[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Schoene Maria vs. Kovalevskaya  Ekaterina, Germany, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3 Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nc4 b5
{ Forcing the knight to move again. This is overwhelmingly the most popular move.   Instead  8...Nf6  runs into  9.Bg5  with the threat to take on  f6  . }
9. Ne3 Nf6 10. a3
{ By preventing Black from expanding with ...b4, White attempts to keep control of the position. }
10... O-O 11. g3 Be6 12. Bg2 Qd7
{ In my repertoire, I recommend  12...Rc8  but the game continuation is also very sensible, claiming control over an important diagonal and connecting the rooks. }
13. O-O Rac8
{ By the way, instead of this, the bad-bishop bounce comes into consideration here -  13...Bd8  The bishop will find a good spot on b6. }
14. f4
{ I was keen to look at this game exactly because White makes this move, and in my experience, it is a common push. However, just because it is common doesn't mean it is good. Black's kingside position is strong, there are simply no weaknesses, whereas it is White that is actually running a risk because pawns are disappearing from in front of the king. In short, when playing with Black, hold on to what is good about your position @@StartBracket@@safe king, well-coordinated pieces, strong pawn structure@@EndBracket@@ and look forward to a stinging counter-attack. }
14... exf4
{ White had a semi-threat of playing the pawn to f5, creating a pawn wedge on the kingside while also closing the centre. The exchange avoids that and looks forward to when White's centre will be vulnerable. }
15. gxf4 Bh3
{ Black had two good alternatives:  15...Bd8   Once more the bishop finds its way to b6, taking aim at the kingside, if  16.f5  Bc4  and the knight finds a great square on e5.   15...Rfe8  is also sensible. The bishop can choose whether it dips back to d8 or f8. }
16. Rf2
{ White would have done better to play  16.Qf3  Bxg2  17.Qxg2  to bring the queen to the kingside. From g2 it also protects the e4 pawn. However, Black's position is still playable after  17...Rfe8 }
16... Rfe8 17. Bxh3 Qxh3
{ The queen is a thorn in White's side. The best she can do is go for an exchange - but that leaves the e4 pawn and c2 pawn as targets. }
18. Qd3 Bd8 19. Ned5 { 19.Nf5  is better. } 19... Qxd3 20. cxd3 Nxd5 21. Nxd5
Ne7
{ Exchanging off the knight emphasises Black's lead in development: White's queenside pieces are still on their starting squares. }
22. Nxe7+ Rxe7 23. Kg2 Bb6 24. Re2 Rec7
{ Taking control over the only open file: Black is better. } 25. Be3 Bxe3 26.
Rxe3 Rc2+ 27. Kg3 Rxb2 28. d4 Kf8 29. Rd1 Rcc2 30. h3 Rg2+ 31. Kh4 Rbf2
{ White's pawn weaknesses came home to roost. This final position illustrates another problem with the f-pawn advance: there is nothing to block the seventh rank.  If White advances the f-pawn, the stakes are raised, but have faith. Keep the kingside firm and trust in counter-attacking moves rather than defence. A mistake by White could have fatal consequences. }
