6... a6 7. Na3 Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. Nc4 b5
{ Forcing the knight to move again. This is overwhelmingly the most popular move.   Instead  8...Nf6  runs into  9.Bg5  with the threat to take on  f6  . }
9. Ne3 Nf6 10. g3 h5
{ Let's go! Played by Carlsen and a speciality of Moiseenko @@StartBracket@@a renowned expert on the Kalashnikov@@EndBracket@@. This already puts White in something of a dilemma: should he block this advance with h3, h4, or just ignore it?   For the record, the more orthodox  10...O-O  has been seen more often and is perfectly playable. }
11. Bg2 h4 12. O-O Rb8
{ A mysterious move! The rook often belongs here in the Kalashnikov. When the knight lands on d5 there is always a danger of a knight fork on b6 or c7, and this takes away some of that jeopardy. The rook also supports the b-pawn making it easier to advance, or perhaps even capture if White advances the a-pawn. It is also a waiting move: White can't do much else here than plant the knight on d5, and we want to be able to exchange that off.   That's why the 'natural'  12...Be6  isn't appropriate here: after  13.Ncd5  we would lose a piece after  13...Nxd5  14.exd5  . Notice that in these lines Black holds back with the h-pawn: later on, it might advance to h3, but exchanging is also an option. Let's see how White reacts first. That's also the reason that Black is delaying castling: the rook could still prove useful on h8. With the centre relatively closed, the king can live in the middle for the moment. }
13. Ncd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nd4 15. Qd3 g6 16. c3 Nf5 17. a4 hxg3
{ In the course, I recommend  17...bxa4  18.Rxa4  Nxe3  19.Qxe3  Bd7  but in this game Black also gains the initiative and succeeds in exploiting the attack on the h-file in style. }
18. hxg3
{ Always a difficult decision for White knowing which way to recapture: f or h pawn?   18.fxg3  leaves the a7-g1 diagonal open and Black has more control in the centre. The e5 pawn cannot be challenged, for example. }
18... Kf8
{ Very sneaky! There is no need to castle: the king finds a safe square on g7 and the rook remains on the h-file. }
19. axb5 axb5 20. Nc2 Kg7 21. Nb4 Qg8 { A rare manoeuvre, but pretty cool! }
22. Nc6 Qh7
{ Right from the opening White's king is under pressure. Mate in one is threatened. With best play White should still be able to hold the position, but it is frightening to play with the queen at such close quarters. }
23. Re1 Rb7 24. Qf3 Bf6 25. Ra8 Ne7 26. Be3
{ The computer thinks that White is in the game after  26.Kf1  Qh2  27.g4  but to my human eyes, it still looks very scary after  27...Qh4  28.Re4  Bg5 }
26... Qh2+ 27. Kf1 Bf5 { with a devastating check threatened on d3. } 28. Rea1
Rxa8 29. Rxa8 Bd3+ 30. Ke1 e4 31. Qf4 g5 32. Qg4 Qxg2 { Game over! } 33. Nxe7
Qh1+ 34. Kd2 Rxe7 35. Bxg5 e3+ 36. Bxe3+ Bg6 37. Qc8 Qxd5+ 38. Kc1 Qh1+ 39. Kd2
Qd5+ 40. Kc1 Qh1+ 41. Kd2 Rxe3
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bqk2r/4bppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/2N1N1P1/PPP2P1P/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@  10...h5  is worth checking carefully, looking not just at this game, but White's responses  11.h3  and  11.h4  . See }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nepomniachtchi  Ian vs. Carlsen Magnus, Abidjan, 2019."]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. N1c3
{ At this point Black can play  6...Nf6  and transpose into a Sveshnikov, but we want to keep the game along pure Kalashnikov lines. }
6... a6 7. Na3 Be7
{ This simple developing move has been played by Carlsen, Nakamura, Radjabov, Ivanchuk, Shirov, and many other luminaries of the chess world. In recent times this has been the move of choice for most strong players, but  7...b5  used to be the most popular continuation. It is certainly worth looking at, but a bit too committal for my taste. I think it is better to hang back with the b-pawn for the moment.   7...Be6  is also worth investigating, and finally  7...Nf6  will probably transpose back into a Sveshnikov after  8.Bg5  .   In fact, that gives us a clue as to why  7...Be7  is played: White is unable to play Bg5, so Black is hoping to retain more control over d5. }
8. g3 Nf6 9. Bg2 b5
{ Instead of this,  9...Bg4  is an awkward move to handle - see the repertoire }
10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 Nb8
{ Here is the reason I wanted to show this game: after the exchange on d5 we have arrived at a position with a very common pawn structure. Instead of a piece, White has a pawn on d5 which changes the nature of the position. This is such a common scenario, as you will see through the repertoire. }
12. O-O Nd7 13. c4
{ Pawn structure determines strategy. White has a four versus three majority on the queenside and, typically, that is where White will want to generate play, using the space advantage that the pawn on d5 confers. Black, on the other hand, will want to generate play on the kingside with the four versus three pawn majority. As you can imagine, in such positions, time is of the essence: who will power through first? }
13... O-O
{ Carlsen already recognises the urgency of the situation and prefers to complete development rather than engage with White's play.   Instead,  13...bxc4  14.Nxc4  a5  @@StartBracket@@to stop b4 and Na5-c6@@EndBracket@@  15.Bd2  O-O  16.Rc1  feels as though White is developing well on the queenside. }
14. cxb5
{ By the way, Black could also embark on kingside play immediately with  14...f5  If  15.bxa6  Bxa6  and it will take some time before White is able to get play going on the queenside. }
14... axb5 15. Nc2 { 15.Nxb5  would be met by  15...Ba6  winning material. }
15... f5 16. Nb4 Bf6 17. Nc6 Qe8 18. a4
{ The position is brewing nicely. Both sides have developed their own play: White can be happy with the knight on c6 and is now opening the queenside; Black tip-toes around the knight and has strong centre pawns. Game on. }
18... Nc5
{ The computer recommendation is:  18...bxa4  19.Rxa4  Ba6  20.Re1  Nc5  21.Ra5  e4  followed by establishing a piece on d3. All Black's minor pieces stand well. }
19. Be3 Nxa4 20. Qc2 Bd7 21. b3 f4
{ 21...Nc5  22.Rxa8  Qxa8  23.Bxc5  dxc5  24.Qxc5  would have swung the game in White's favour. }
22. bxa4 fxe3 23. axb5 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Bg5 { Threatening to take on f2. } 25. b6
{ Nepo goes all in, backing the b-pawn to go all the way, but allowing Black in on the kingside, to some extent.   If  25.fxe3  Bxe3+  26.Kh1  Rf2  27.Qb3  Bb6  The rook is great on f2 and the dark-squared bishop - apparently the 'bad' bishop, once more proves what a superb piece it can be, controlling an important diagonal, attacking and defending simultaneously. }
25... exf2+ 26. Kh1 Bc8 27. Rf1 Qf7 28. Qe2 e4 29. h4
{ If  29.Bxe4  Bh3  30.Bg2  Bxg2+  31.Kxg2  Qxd5+  wins.   White's best is  29.Qxe4  Ba6  30.Qe6  Bxf1  31.Bxf1  Kh8  and apparently with precise play White can hold, but this is somewhat academic given the rough and tumble nature of a rapid game @@StartBracket@@and indeed this kind of position@@EndBracket@@. }
29... e3
{ An extraordinary move. Carlsen has judged that his pawns will be worth a piece.   29...Bh6?  30.Bxe4  Bh3  31.Ne7+!  Kh8   31...Qxe7  32.Bxh7+  32.Bg2  Bxg2+  33.Kxg2  In this case the knight on e7 defends the d5 pawn. }
30. hxg5 Re8
{ Holding the pawn and preparing to take the pawn on g5 with the queen followed by a deadly check on h6. }
31. Kh2 Bg4 { 31...Qg6?  32.Bh3 } 32. Qxg4 e2 33. b7 Qxb7 34. Rxf2 e1=Q
{ Magnus has won the race but is it a pyrrhic victory? He still needs to quell White's pieces on the kingside. }
35. Qf5 Qe3 36. Rf3 Qe2 37. Nd4 Qe5 38. Qg4 Qbxd5 39. Nf5 Qde6 40. Qh5 Qg6 41.
Qg4 h5 42. Qc4+ d5 43. Qb5 Qxg5 44. Qd7 h4 45. Rf1 hxg3+ 46. Kg1 g6 47. Bxd5+
Kh8
{ The fun is over and White resigned.  This is an excellent example of strategy with such a pawn structure. Both sides were intent on pursuing their own plans and neither blinked. Carlsen strove with all his might to push forward his kingside pawn majority, although sometimes it can be worth pausing and seeing what is happening on the other side of the board @@StartBracket@@see move 18@@EndBracket@@. It took precise calculation to execute the kingside attack, but in general what is important is to recognise the broad thrust of strategy: attempt to advance the e and f-pawns. }
