[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Quparadze Giga vs. Rapport Richard, Riadh, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

{ The opening starts out as a Sicilian Taimanov but soon transposes into a normal 6. c4 Kalashnikov. }
1. e4 c5 2. Ne2 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4 a6 7. N5c3 g6 8. Bf4
Nf6 9. Be2 e5 10. Be3 Be6 { We are back on familiar territory. } 11. Nd5 Bxd5
12. cxd5 Nd4
{ An important moment in the game. This is a common scenario: White plays the knight into  d5  , Black exchanges, the pawn recaptures and the knight on  c6  has a choice, forward or back? It is possible to play  12...Ne7  , which is satisfactory, but there is a danger that White will be able to use the space advantage and the bishop pair in the long term. In short, it's a bit passive. Leaping forward is more provocative: White has difficult questions to answer. }
13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Qxd4 Bg7
{ What has Black got for the pawn? Dark squares! That wonderful bishop on g7 has no opponent. And don't forget the open e and c-files. }
15. Nc3 O-O 16. O-O Re8 { The first threat: ...Nxe4. } 17. Qd3 Qb6
{ Another threat: the pawn on b2. It's not just the bishop on g7 that has a free run on the dark squares now that one of the bishops has disappeared from the board. }
18. Rab1 Rac8 19. a3 Nd7
{ The final piece spins into battle. It is already clear that Black has more than ample compensation for the pawn. }
20. Bg4 Ne5 21. Qd1 Rc4 22. Be2 Rd4 23. Qc2 Nd7 24. b4 Rc8 25. Qb3 Rd2 26. Na4
Qd4 27. Bg4 f5 28. Bh3 Rcc2
{ Total domination. It is fitting that the breakthrough occurs on a dark square. }
29. Rbd1 Qxf2+ 30. Kh1 Rxd1 31. Rxd1 b5 32. exf5 gxf5 33. Qd3 Ne5 34. Qxf5 bxa4
35. Qe6+ Kh8 36. Qxd6 Re2 37. Qc5 Re1+ 38. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 39. Qg1 Qxg1+ 40. Kxg1
Bf8 41. Bc8 Bxb4 42. Bxa6 Bxa3 43. Kf2 Bc5+ 44. Ke2 a3
{ Prepare to be bold in the Kalashnikov. Sacrificing a pawn with ...Nd4 can be wonderful if White's dark-squared bishop drops in the process. }
