[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Steinberg Nitzan vs. Cheparinov Ivan, Tornelo ,2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4
{ White clamps the middle of the board and makes absolutely sure of squashing the pawn break ...d5. Think again! As we shall see, Black has devilishly dynamic chances and in the mainline, that is precisely the pawn move we will be looking to unleash.   That said, we should not underestimate this version of the Maroczy Bind: it is important we understand how to create counterplay or Black will get squashed.   Aside from  6.N1c3  , this is the other main line of the Kalashnikov Variation. }
6... Be6
{ As usual, this is an excellent square for the bishop, covering the d5 square and also looking at the c4 pawn.   The older way of playing this position was  6...Be7  7.N1c3  a6  8.Na3  Be6  9.Nc2  Bg5  10.Be2  Bxc1  11.Rxc1  . While it is positionally sound to exchange off these bishops I feel it loses too much time, allowing White to develop rapidly and establish strong control in the centre.   For reference, I invite you to look up the game Carlsen-Hou, Tata Steel 2015 where Black was reduced to passivity. }
7. N1c3
{ The vast majority bring out the knight here, conforming to standard opening principles. However, move-order can be fairly fluid in this line: bishops are developed at different times to e2 or e3 and sometimes elsewhere.   7.Be2  and  7.Bd3  are examined in separate chapters. }
7... a6 8. Na3 g6 9. Be2 Bg7 10. Nc2 Rc8 11. b3 Nf6 12. O-O O-O 13. Be3
{ Black's setup is my main recommendation against the Maroczy Bind with 6. c4. At the moment White's position appears solid and secure, but the next move is a hammer. }
13... b5
{ This pawn break is a crucial move in the battle against White's Maroczy Bind. If White does not react, an exchange will leave the c4 pawn isolated and weak. If the pawn is captured, the c-file opens and Black will have the option to break with ...d5. }
14. cxb5 axb5 15. Bxb5 Ne7
{ In the repertoire I recommend  15...Na7  , but this is also dangerous - as the game continuation demonstrates. White's knights on c3 and c2 are lined up beautifully for the rook on c8. It is difficult for White to control the tactics in such a position. }
16. Na4
{ if White plays the 'natural' move  16.Qd2  Black wins a piece with  16...Qc7 }
16... Qa5
{ Another option is to break immediately with  16...d5  17.exd5  Nexd5  What a transformation. Which side now controls the centre? Once again we see how the ...d5 pawn break liberates Black's pieces. }
17. Bd3 d5 18. exd5 Nexd5 19. Bd2 Qa7
{ Black dominates the centre. That's partly to do with the extra centre pawn on e5, but also Black's superb minor pieces. White's extra pawn on the queenside plays no meaningful role in the game. }
20. Ne3 Nf4
{ When one controls the centre, it is possible to turn towards the kingside. }
21. Bc4 Rfd8
{ According to my computer,  21...Ne4  is even stronger, with the idea  22.Bxe6  fxe6!?  bringing the king's rook into play on the f-file. It looks ugly to break the pawns in this way, but the computer lines convince me of the power of Black's pieces. }
22. Qc2
{ 22.Bxe6  Nxe6  would have been a better way for White to play, although there is still pressure. }
22... Qb7 { So often a wonderful diagonal for the queen in the Kalashnikov. }
23. f3 e4 { Open the diagonals! } 24. Rae1 Nd3
{ Always good to see an octopus knight causing terror in White's camp. } 25.
Re2 exf3 26. Rxf3 Ne5 27. Rf1 Nxc4 28. bxc4 Ne4 29. Bc1 Qc6 30. Bb2 Bh6 31. Nc3
{ In his eagerness to bring the knight back from the edge, White allows a tactic. }
31... Rd2 32. Qb3
{ 32.Rxd2  Bxe3+  33.Rdf2  Nxf2  34.Rxf2  Qxc4  Pieces will drop. } 32... Nc5
33. Qb5 Qxb5 34. cxb5 Rxe2 35. Nxe2 Bxe3+ 36. Kh1 Nd3
{ Black is a piece up with a continuing initiative. Time for White to bow out. It is fitting that even at the end Black's pieces dominate the middle of the board. This game is a wonderful lesson in how Black is able to break down White's centre with two powerful pawn breaks: ...b5 and ...d5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Anand Viswanathan vs. Maghsoodloo Parham, Online Olym Div Top-A, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4
{ White clamps the middle of the board and makes absolutely sure of squashing the pawn break ...d5. Think again! As we shall see, Black has devilishly dynamic chances and in the mainline, that is precisely the pawn move we will be looking to unleash.   That said, we should not underestimate this version of the Maroczy Bind: it is important we understand how to create counterplay or Black will get squashed.   Aside from  6.N1c3  , this is the other main line of the Kalashnikov Variation. }
6... Be6
{ As usual, this is an excellent square for the bishop, covering the d5 square and also looking at the c4 pawn.   The older way of playing this position was  6...Be7  7.N1c3  a6  8.Na3  Be6  9.Nc2  Bg5  10.Be2  Bxc1  11.Rxc1  . While it is positionally sound to exchange off these bishops I feel it loses too much time, allowing White to develop rapidly and establish strong control in the centre.   For reference, I invite you to look up the game Carlsen-Hou, Tata Steel 2015 where Black was reduced to passivity. }
7. N1c3
{ The vast majority bring out the knight here, conforming to standard opening principles. However, move-order can be fairly fluid in this line: bishops are developed at different times to e2 or e3 and sometimes elsewhere.   7.Be2  and  7.Bd3  are examined in separate chapters. }
7... a6 8. Na3 g6 9. Nc2
{ Move order is flexible. Most players like to play the knight to c2 to cover the d4 square - and I think that is the most sensible.   Others prefer to develop with  9.Be3  or  9.Be2  . Very often these lines transpose. I will point out where these variations have independent significance. From Black's viewpoint matters are much clearer: in most cases, the next moves will be ...Bg7, ...Nf6, ...O-O - and then let's think again! }
9... Bg7 10. Be3 Nf6 11. Be2 Rc8 12. b3 O-O 13. O-O b5
{ That move! It is so important to break down White's pawn structure. } 14.
cxb5 Ne7
{ Another testing continuation for White to handle.   14...axb5  15.Bxb5  Ne7  was played in Steinberg-Cheparinov, while  15...Na7  was my repertoire recommendation. }
15. Bd2 axb5 16. Bxb5 Qb6 17. Na3 Rxc3
{ Very bold. Black sacrifices the exchange in order to wipe out the pawn on e4.   17...d5  18.exd5  Nfxd5  is also a strong way for Black to play, taking control of the centre very much in the way that Cheparinov did. }
18. Bxc3 Nxe4 19. Bb2 d5
{ A powerful centre. Black's plan is to roll them down the board and then turn towards White's king. }
20. Be2 d4
{ There are pros and cons to this move. For Anand, the opportunity to bring the knight in from the cold must have been welcome.   20...Nd6  was an alternative strategy, and only then roll the d-pawn. }
21. Nc4 Bxc4 22. Bxc4 Nd6 23. Ba3 Nef5 24. Rc1 e4 25. Bc5 Qd8 26. Re1 Re8 27.
b4 Nxc4 28. Rxc4 e3 { White's kingside opens. } 29. fxe3 Nxe3 30. Qa4 Re6 31.
Rcc1 Qd5 32. Re2 d3
{ This was an online rapid game, so blunders, particularly at this stage of the game, are to be expected. }
33. Rd2
{ 33.Rxe3!  Bd4  looks like it is winning, but White has an unusual defence that flips the game:  34.Qa7! }
33... Bd4
{ Black dominates the centre and the game now resumes its course: White cannot withstand the kingside attack. }
34. Kh1 Nxg2 35. Qb3 { 35.Rxg2  Re2  wins. } 35... Qa8
{ It is telling that a player as strong as Anand was unable to control the tactics in such a position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Pichot Alan vs. Giri Anish, FTX Crypto Cup Prelim, 2021"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 5. Nb5 d6 6. c4
{ White clamps the middle of the board and makes absolutely sure of squashing the pawn break ...d5. Think again! As we shall see, Black has devilishly dynamic chances and in the mainline, that is precisely the pawn move we will be looking to unleash.   That said, we should not underestimate this version of the Maroczy Bind: it is important we understand how to create counterplay or Black will get squashed.   Aside from  6.N1c3  , this is the other main line of the Kalashnikov Variation. }
6... g6 7. N1c3 a6 8. Na3 Bg7 9. Nc2 Nf6 10. Be2 O-O 11. Be3 Be6 12. O-O Rc8
13. f3
{ The e-pawn gets some extra support, but it allows a new possibility for Black.  13.b3  is covered in two other games in this chapter, Steinberg-Cheparinov and Anand-Maghsoodloo. }
13... Nh5 14. Nd5
{ If  14.Qd2  Nf4  anyway, as  15.Bxf4  exf4  rips open the long diagonal for the bishop and don't forget the check on b6. Conclusion: White should not give up the dark-squared bishop. }
14... Bxd5
{ Giri makes a practical choice and eliminates the knight immediately, however   14...Nf4  also came strongly into consideration. Exchanging off the e2 bishop followed by ...f5 is a reasonable plan. And  15.Nxf4  exf4  16.Bxf4  Qb6+  17.Rf2  Qxb2  gives Black's pieces plenty of play. }
15. Qxd5
{ A mistake.  15.cxd5  would have been better when  15...Nd4  is the boldest response @@StartBracket@@see in this chapter for another example of the ...Nd4 pawn sacrifice@@EndBracket@@:  16.Nxd4  exd4  17.Bxd4  Bxd4+  18.Qxd4  Nf4  19.Rf2  h5   19...Qg5  20.Kh1  Nxe2  21.Rxe2  Rc1+  22.Rxc1  Qxc1+  23.Qg1  Rc8  is a good alternative. Controlling the only open file, Black cannot be worse.  20.Kh1  h4  gives good play for the pawn. }
15... Nd4
{ Once again, the knight hits the outpost, supported by the bishop on g7. In this case, White's queen finds itself in trouble. }
16. Bd3
{ A furious attack is unleashed after  16.Nxd4?  exd4  17.Bd2   17.Bxd4  Nf4  wins  Rc5  18.Qxb7  d3  19.Bxd3  Bd4+  20.Kh1   20.Rf2  Qh4  21.Raf1  Ng3-+  Ng3+  21.hxg3  Rh5  checkmate. }
16... b5
{ Cuts off the queen's path to a5 and as a bonus breaks down the c4 pawn, as we have seen in other Maroczy games. }
17. Nxd4 { If  17.b3  Qd7  followed by ...Rc5 traps the queen. } 17... exd4 18.
Bg5 { 18.Bxd4  Nf4  wins material. } 18... Qb6
{ Covering b7, so that ...Rc5 is a threat. } 19. cxb5 Rc5 20. Qb3 Rxg5 21. bxa6
Qxb3 22. axb3
{ Black has won a piece, but must still play energetically to bring the point home. }
22... Nf4 { The knight comes in from the cold and plays a crucial role. } 23.
Bc4 Rxg2+ 24. Kh1 Rxb2 25. Rfb1 Rc2 26. Rc1 d3 27. Rxc2 Bxa1 28. Rc1 Bd4 29.
Rd1 Bc5 30. h4 Kg7 31. Kh2 Kf6 32. Kg3 Ke5
{ The knight is held on f4 and the extra piece is secure. Black can force a win by opening the g-file and beginning a checkmating attack with the rook and the minor pieces.  The key points to remember from this game: the outposts on f4 and d4 are ready for Black's knight. }
