[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Strejczek Dariusz vs. Zhigalko Sergei, Katowice, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e5 6. Nb3
{ The position arose from a Sveshnikov, but can commonly arise from a Kalashnikov @@StartBracket@@@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.Nf3  Nc6  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  e5  5.Nb3  Nf6  6.Nc3  Bb4  etc@@EndBracket@@. If White declines to play Nb5, then I already believe that Black has equalised the position. That is certainly borne out by this game. }
6... Bb4 { Excellent move, putting immediate pressure on the e4 pawn. } 7. Bd3
O-O
{ In the repertoire, I recommend  7...d5  8.exd5  Nxd5  9.Bd2  Nxc3  10.bxc3  Bd6  which I believe offers Black excellent chances of an advantage. Nevertheless, it is hard to complain about such a natural move as castling. }
8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3
{ Instead of breaking with ...d5, Black continues with a very different strategy that is also promising: damaging the queenside pawns and setting up a strong pawn chain in the middle  @@StartBracket@@d6 and e5@@EndBracket@@. There are some similarities with Black's strategy in the Nimzo-Indian Defence. }
9... d6 10. h3 Re8
{ Black must have been concerned about White playing f4, but actually, the natural developing move  10...Be6  was fine:  11.f4  exf4  12.Bxf4  Ne5  .  A beautiful blockading square, shutting out the bishop on d3   If  13.Bg5   13.Nd4  Qc7  is also comfortable for Black.  Qb6+  14.Nd4  Nfd7  escapes the pin with a rock-solid position. }
11. Bg5
{ 11.f4  exf4  12.Bxf4  Nxe4  13.Bxe4  Rxe4  14.Bxd6  Re6  Is certainly better for Black in view of White's damaged pawns. }
11... h6 12. Bh4 { Is the pin problematic? Not at all! } 12... g5
{ This cuts through White's strategy. Black can get away with this 'weakening' of the kingside because the centre is closed, White is unable to open lines on the kingside, and it is impossible for him to transfer minor pieces over to the kingside. More than that, this pawn thrust allows Black to take the initiative on the kingside. }
13. Bg3 Be6 14. f3
{ Black has two possible plans: play ...Rc8, move the knight on c6 and target the c3 pawn; or attack on the kingside. }
14... Nh5 15. Bf2 Nf4 16. Be3 Rc8 { It looks like Black is going to do both! }
17. Bxf4
{ It was difficult for White to find an active plan, but this grants Black an easy attack on the g-file. }
17... gxf4 18. Kh2 Kh7 19. Rg1 Rg8 20. Nc1 Qh4 21. Qe1 Rg3
{ 21...Rxg2+  wins immediately:  22.Rxg2   22.Kxg2  Rg8+  23.Kf1  Rxg1+  Qxe1 }
22. Qf1 Rcg8 23. Ne2 R3g5 24. Qe1
{ A blunder in a bad position.   24.Rb1  b6  25.a3  Rh5  26.Rd1  Rg3  is a good way to finish off the attack: ...Bxh3 is coming soon. }
24... Rxg2+
{ 24...Rxg2+  25.Rxg2  Qxh3+  26.Kg1  Qxg2  In general, the pawn structure that results from the opening is more than fine for Black. However, bear in mind that the dark-squared bishop is White's only potential asset and that the pin from g5 can be an issue. This game shows that very often that pin can be broken by simply playing ...g5 and there are few consequences - certainly not for Black. }
*

